<TEXT>
a state textbook committee on wednesday rejected 
a reading series opposed by fundamentalists because of references 
to ghosts and scary themes like child abandonment the publisher 
called the vote censorship 
its a blessing proclaimed eric coloney a peachtree city 
parent opposed to the impressions reading series 
the 138 vote against the series virtually assures that most 
school systems will not use it the state board of education will 
make final decisions in november schools can use books that arent 
on the approved state list but must use local funds to buy them 
several committee members expressed disappointment at the vote 
against the series which publisher harcourt brace jovanovich inc 
designed as an innovative reading program for teachers it uses the 
socalled whole language approach in which pupils study real 
childrens literature rather than sample paragraphs and phonics 
exercises 
i do feel like the specialinterest people influenced the 
textbook selection process said committee member lynne donehoo 
a bibb county counselor 
mrs donehoo said that when parents and teachers in her area 
reviewed impressions none objected to the content 
but with the highprofile complaints against the series 
including 190 opposition phone calls to the state department of 
education in recent days committee members took a harder look at 
the series she said 
only 22 of 822 stories mention ghosts or goblins and most of 
the troubling issues raised in the stories from adoption to 
sexism to witchcraft are addressed constructively in the 
teachers manual said jan spalding director of sales support 
services for harcourt brace 
selections ranging from laura ingalls wilders little house on 
the prairie to speeches from martin luther king jr both of 
which appear in the books got little attention as the committee 
focused on witches child abandonment chants and scary 
pictures she said 
joyce washingtonbray a reading specialist in marietta and 
member of the state committee that voted against the books said 
the content could detract from teaching 
when its this stuff about outer space material that is eerie 
that muddies it up for thinking and reading ms 
washingtonbray said 
said pat turner an assistant principal from americus city 
schools in some ways id say we just went through a witch 
hunt 
