<TEXT>
a nasa team trying to pinpoint 
columbias dangerous hydrogen leaks has narrowed the list of 
possible sources to 83 
any combination might actually be the culprit said william 
lenoir head of nasas space flight program 
a hydrogen buildup in the shuttles engine compartment during 
fueling last week forced nasa to call off its fourth attempt to 
send columbia on an astronomy mission three of the postponements 
were caused by hydrogen leaks 
the shuttle is grounded until all leaks are found and fixed a 
ninemember investigative team assigned to the problem is 
scrutinizing every item in columbias crowded engine compartment as 
a possible source of leaks 
even if the first thing they do is find a big roaring leak 
they will worry about how do we fix that leak but they will 
continue everywhere else to look for things that might also be 
leaking lenoir said wednesday 
workers will remove insulation from each suspected part and then 
flush the system with nonflammable roomtemperature helium 
lenoir said 
if no leaks are found the process will be repeated with a 
different crew and equipment to be absolutely sure we havent 
missed anything he said 
so far columbias leaks have appeared only when the shuttles 
external tank is filled with highly flammable liquid hydrogen at 
supercold temperatures which might cause shrinkage of a metal 
part and form the leak 
to test for that possibility the external tank will twice be 
filled with cold liquid hydrogen around midoctober and in 
november about a dozen tv cameras will be placed inside the engine 
compartment for both tests 
nasa meanwhile is working to send discovery aloft oct 6 with 
a satellite to study the suns poles the shuttle must fly within 
the following 2 weeks or else wait more than a year for the 
planets to be in the right alignment 
the space agency plans no tanking test for discovery the only 
shuttle in which hydrogen leaks have not been found such a check 
would take five days 
a tanking test will be performedon atlantis before its early 
november flight hydrogen leaks were detected on the spacecraft in 
june 
lenoir said that he is hopeful columbia can be back on track in 
december but that there is no timetable 
theyre not driven by schedule they are to go out and find 
the leak find all of the leaks and then we can get on with it 
he said 
</TEXT>
