<TEXT>
carnegie hall tonight begins a seasonlong 
celebration of its 100th birthday secure as a centerpiece of 
american culture one generation after it nearly fell victim to the 
wreckers ball 
the auditorium on west 57th street still sparkling from a 50 
million facelift four years ago will be host in the coming months 
to the best and brightest of the music world from pops to placido 
domingo from jazz to jessye norman 
opening night honors go to the los angeles philharmonic 
conductor andre previn and violinist itzhak perlman the second 
night also by the orchestra will present the first of 13 pieces 
of music commissioned by carnegie for its centennial season thats 
the largest number of commissioned works ever in one season by an 
american presenting organization 
the second night premiere will be angelus based on the 
chiming of bells and composed by steven stucky last december a 
month before he was 85 sir michael tippett completed 
byzantium which will have its premiere in april by the chicago 
symphony with conductor sir georg solti making his final visit to 
carnegie as music director of that orchestra 
its probably the most extraordinary season that any hall has 
ever had violinist isaac stern said 
stern has been president of carnegie hall since 1960 when he 
saved it from the fate of being torn down so an office building 
could rise on the corner of 57th street and 7th avenue 
carnegie hall when youre playing in form makes a 
performance larger than life its an enormously powerful hall and 
it does give even average performers a glamour and power they 
wouldnt have in other halls stern said in an interview shortly 
before his 70th birthday in july 
carnegie was the place where you came to prove whether you 
belonged or not for that reason it was very necessary to play 
there it still is it has been the crown proving place for 
every single orchestra every one every conductor every pianist 
singer violinist cellist jazz player comedian pop singer 
andrew carnegie donated 2 million approximately ninetenths of 
the cost of construction but it was leopold damrosch founder of 
both the symphony society the citys second orchestra after the 
new york philharmonic and the oratorio society who felt new york 
needed another large hall besides the metropolitan opera his son 
walter music director of both organizations in 1887 happened to 
sail that year on the same ship as carnegie and his bride who were 
on their honeymoon by the time the ship reached europe carnegie 
had agreed to build a fine concert hall in new york 
ten concerts starting april 26 will lead up to the centennial 
date itself may 5 the day will start with a morning concert by 
eight choruses conducted by robert shaw the new york philharmonic 
conducted by zubin mehta and leonard bernstein will perform at 4 
pm take a dinner break and resume 
soloists at that concert will include sopranos leontyne price 
and miss norman mezzosoprano marilyn horne tenor domingo 
pianist rudolf serkin violinists stern and pinchas zukerman 
cellists mstislav rostropovich and yoyo ma and the empire brass 
quintet 
carnegie hall is the center from which the entire development 
of american music came stern said nothing happened in this 
country that didnt come through carnegie 
the hall has been acclaimed throughout its history for its 
architecture and acoustics 
during the most recent renovation workmen closed a hole that 
had been cut in the ceiling over the stage for a movie in the 
1940s that and some other changes prompted some critics to 
complain that the halls warm acoustics had been damaged in 
response a row of freestanding panels was built that can be 
placed along the back wall behind orchestras 
whats important to stern is that carnegie hall now restored 
as much as possible to its 1891 look with airconditioning 
improved and less street noise coming in stands for another 100 
years 
its something to hold on to some connection with mans 
involvement with education with the quality of civilization those 
are the things which are worthwhile 
</TEXT>
