<TEXT>
editors note this report is one of a series on the german 
countdown to unity on oct 3 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
guenter grass and other authors are 
among the last holdout opponents to unification firing salvos of 
dissent that have not damaged the unity express but have fractured 
the german intelligenstia 
the debate has triggered a furious philosophical feud over 
whether star east german writers like christa wolf indirectly 
bolstered the hardline communist state by not actively opposing 
it 
some leftist german writers have charged that the real 
beneficiaries of unification are not the common people but 
businessmen and politicians who stand to reap financial and 
political profits 
but many critics maintain that grass and other members of 
germanys mostly leftist literary pantheon are hopelessly out of 
touch with the rest of the population 
the foremost feature of these people is an unbelievable 
vanity enno von loewenstern editorial writer for the 
conservative die welt newspaper said in an interview if the 
common folk refuse to follow their line they have not wakened to 
their true consciousness 
conservative writers from both germanys have expressed similar 
views 
the debate began soon after the first cracks appeared in the 
berlin wall last fall 
wolf novelist stefan heym and other east germans published a 
manifesto warning against a sellout of material and moral 
values to their rich west german neighbors 
the message was that east germany with a new democratic 
government and freedom for the people was something worth 
preserving 
west german critics asked why the same east german intellectuals 
hadnt been as loud with critical pronouncements during stalinist 
rule 
the ultimate question was had east german intellectuals 
acquiesced to the repressive rule for the special privileges 
bestowed upon artists and writers 
the debate turned angrier when wolf published an 
autobiographical novella called what remains in which she 
suggested she had been hounded by the stasi secret police in the 
late 1970s 
a critic for die welt questioned whether wolf has the right to 
portray herself as a martyr because she had to endure three stasi 
observers sitting in a car across from her apartment 
many people have lived through this and worse the 
critic said 
grass and other leftist west german authors have rushed to 
wolfs defense 
he has compared the campaign against wolf to an inquisition and 
said it could do irreparable damage to the german intellectual 
community 
grass has accused wolfs critics of hypocrisy pointing out that 
no one seemed to mind during the communist years that her status 
allowed her to deliver readings and lectures to enrapt listeners 
and reviewers in the west 
the debate goes beyond whether east german intellectuals chose a 
cozy life under communist rule over trying to bring about real 
change 
at the heart of all the arguing is unification itself 
this spring millions of east germans loudly voiced their 
support for unification by shouting we are one people at 
election rallies 
german intellectuals heard the cry but many leftist writers say 
unity is a mistake 
grass evoking the third reich and auschwitz at one point said 
a united germany would be a danger to itself and other nations 
in in interview in early september grass said he favored a 
confederation between the two germanys but not unification 
the previous united german state lasted briefly from 
bismarck to 1945 it was only 70 years and was the unhappiest phase 
in all of german history and in european history as well he 
said 
east german heiner mueller one of europes bestknown 
playwrights and a diehard socialist says the germans destiny has 
been taken from their hands by west german chancellor helmut kohl 
the architect of unification 
whats happening now is an economic conquest of east 
germany he said 
other intellectuals disagree 
martin walser the west german novelist said the east germans 
do control their destiny they could have chosen to create a free 
socialist state as he points out was favored by many 
intellectuals 
i would have said ok if thats what you believe walser 
said in a recent newspaper interview but the people decided on 
something else 
reiner kunze a leading poet who was thrown out of east germany 
in 1977 has scolded grass for his views no one needs to fear 
germany kunze said 
west german patrick sueskind author of the bestselling novel 
perfume has written a new book titled fear of germany in 
which he takes aim at the hoopla and hype accompanying unification 
he said the idea of unity has taken his generation of postwar 
babyboomers by surprise 
we thought we had a grasp on our existence and understood the 
world and now were suddenly confronted with this midlife 
crisis sueskind writes 
we were prepared for impotence for prostate problems false 
teeth menopause for cancer death and the devil but 
definitely not for deutschlandeinigvaterland 
the phrase means germany united fatherland a favorite 
chant at east german election rallies this year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900926-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
house negotiators are reported near agreement 
on legislation to extend the life of the national endowment for the 
arts and let the courts decide whether its grant recipients have 
violated obscenity laws 
i think were going to get a deal said rep pat williams 
dmont a central figure in house bargaining over the fate of the 
embattled federal arts agency 
in an interview tuesday williams predicted that lengthy talks 
with rep e thomas coleman rmo will yield a compromise on the 
obscene art issue that will attract the support of a solid 
majority of house members 
he said the compromise is likely to be patterned after a formula 
the senate labor and human resources committee approved last week 
with strong bipartisan backing 
the senate bill would require the nea to recoup grant money from 
artists who are convicted of using federal funds to produce works 
that violate obscenity laws the guilty artists would be barred 
from receiving further nea grants for at least three years 
on thursday the house tentatively plans to begin what promises 
to be a bruising floor battle over a proposed fiveyear extension 
of the arts endowment whose statutory authority expires sunday 
lawmakers readied no fewer than two dozen amendments most of 
them seeking to prohibit nea support for works that might be 
considered obscene or sacrilegious one proposal would abolish the 
arts endowment altogether 
strict antiobscenity curbs imposed on the endowment last fall 
at the urging of sen jesse helms rnc also will lapse next 
week when the current fiscal year ends unless congress renews them 
in some form 
in a related development the house appropriations committee on 
tuesday rebuffed an attempt by its chairman rep jamie whitten 
dmiss to recommend forbidding the nea to finance any indecent 
antireligious or obscene picture play or writing 
on a voice vote the committee eliminated whittens nonbinding 
proposal from a stopgap bill intended to keep the federal 
government operating at current spending levels for the first three 
weeks of the new fiscal year until oct 20 and to provide 2 
billion for us military operations in the persian gulf 
the effect of the bill later approved and sent to the house 
floor was to continue the nea temporarily at the level of its 
current 171 million budget with the helms antiobscenity curbs 
intact 
rep sidney yates dill argued that whittens antiobscenity 
proposal should be considered later when the committee acts on the 
neas proposed 180 million appropriations bill for next year 
the prospective compromise between williams and coleman 
opposing figures in the nea controversy would leave to the courts 
not the endowment the responsibility for deciding whether 
federally subsidized works are obscene 
coleman previously had proposed forbidding the nea from 
supporting works that meet the supreme courts obscenity standards 
the helms ban went further prohibiting support for any works that 
may be considered obscene including depictions of 
homoeroticism sadomasochism and sexual exploitation of children 
williams said another coleman proposal to shift 60 percent of 
nea grant money to the control of state arts agencies remains in 
dispute he said the compromise bill may include a limited increase 
in the 20 percent of grant funds currently allocated to the states 
colemot return calls seeking comment 
williams a staunch nea supporter is chief sponsor of the bush 
administrations original bill to extend the neas life for five 
years without any antiobscenity restrictions 
congressional sources said the house probably would vote for a 
shorter extension perhaps three or four years to allow congress 
more frequent reviews of nea operations 
rep dick armey rtexas expressed support tuesday for a 
proposed amendment by rep phil crane rill that would abolish 
the nea armey said he found abhorrent the very existence of a 
politically appointed government panel charged with determining 
what art is worthy of funding 
</TEXT>
