<TEXT>
the soviet union in an astonishing speech 
by foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze is suddenly in the 
forefront of the international drive against iraqi president saddam 
hussein while pushing relations with the united states to 
unprecedented heights 
the two superpowers are still haggling over arms control 
measures unless secretary of state james a baker iii achieves a 
sudden breakthrough today in a private meeting with shevardnadze 
two summits may have to be set back 
but with world attention riveted on the united nations and the 
precarious pressure campaign to force iraq to relinquish its 
conquest of kuwait shevardnadze has given president bush all the 
support he could hope to have and then some 
the genial georgian who sits at mikhail s gorbachevs right 
hand in the soviet power structure not only blasted saddam on 
tuesday as a terrorist threatening the new world order but 
suggested his seizure of kuwait might call for a war crimes trial 
those who take hostages employ torture and threaten other 
nations with destruction are engaged in crimes against humanity 
and should be judged by an international tribunal shevardnadze 
said 
moreover the soviet foreign minister raised the prospect of a 
un military force against iraq if the 7weekold economic 
blockade fails to induce saddam to give up the oilrich emirate 
the united nations has the power to suppress acts of 
aggression shevardnadze observed 
the first proposition conjured up images of the nuremberg trials 
of nazi leaders after world war ii the second carried echoes of 
president harry s trumans unsanctioned defense of south korea 
against aggression from the north 
significantly both proposals were sterner than any advanced by 
the bush administration in some ways shevardnadze vaulted past 
the united states in taking the moral high ground against baghdad 
it was a very strong speech canadian foreign minister joe 
clark said afterward it certainly indicates that we are in a new 
era of international affairs 
clark also complimented shevardnadze for the way he chaired 
tuesdays un security council session in which the body voted 
141 to impose an air embargo against iraq it is a dramatic 
demonstration of how much has changed internationally he said 
ussoviet relations have been on the upsurge for years but 
until the soviets withdrew their troops from afghanistan in 1988 
many in washington questioned the sincerity of gorbachevs moves 
even in this new era of good feelings the two sides still are 
struggling to resolve their differences over cutting longrange 
nuclear weapons and reducing their tanks and other conventional 
arms in europe 
failure to agree on nuclear cutbacks could imperil the trip bush 
hoped to take to moscow in december to sign a treaty slashing 
longrange arsenals of bombers submarines and intercontinental 
ballistic missiles the dispute over conventional forces could 
postpone the 35nation summit france proposed to host in paris in 
midnovember 
there is time to rescue both pacts in the meantime cooperation 
on coping with the crisis in the persian gulf is at a maximum 
when bush set out in early august to impose an economic 
stranglehold on saddam he encountered some hesitation from moscow 
soviet support was considered essential for several reasons 
first of all as a permanent member of the un security council 
the soviets could kill any measure against iraq second the united 
states needed the other superpowers support to persuade the world 
the campaign against iraq was not a solo show of force by 
washington 
third the credibility of the campaign would gain immensely if 
it had the support of the soviets since they had been allies of 
iraq 
the soviet hesitation on sanctions recurred in late august when 
the bush administration went back to the security council to 
enforce the sanctions 
again moscows anxieties about inflaming a touchy situation 
yielded to a judgment that saddam must be contained despite the 
risk 
two weeks ago bush and gorbachev agreed in helsinki finland 
that additional measures might be required the imposition of a 
un air blockade was the result 
not too many years ago the soviets were the targets of the sort 
of condemnation shevardnadze heaped on saddam their actions in 
eastern europe and treatment of their own people generated the kind 
of outrage now being visited on iraq 
but now as gorbachev struggles to transform the soviet union 
into a market economy with and to institute political democracy 
shevardnadze appealed to iraqs leaders to obey the demands of 
the law and also of plain common sense to take a responsible and 
human attitude 
he said the soviets are making the appeal as old friends of the 
iraqis 
shevardnadze said the soviets spoke also as a country that 
found the courage to condemn its own wrongdoings against certain 
states in the past 
such admissions are rare on the world diplomatic stage and they 
served to intensify the respect shevardnadze earned with his 
speech 
 
editors note barry schweid is the associated press chief 
diplomatic writer 
