<TEXT>
the bridge of friendship over the danube 
once symbolized comradely communist ties between bulgaria and 
romania but its been a source of tension since authorities began 
cracking down on smugglers 
it can take as long as three days toget across the bridge 
between russe bulgaria and this town 60 miles south of bucharest 
heating up tempers and radiators alike 
under the two countries former communist governments lines 
were virtually nonexistent because travel and the opportunity for 
private trading were strictly limited 
all that changed after last years democratic upheaval 
the romanian and bulgarian economies are in chaos as new 
goverments start steering away from central planning and toward 
freemarket practices and romanians who face shortages of basic 
foods such as bread and sugar at home are going on shopping sprees 
in turkey 
they can even pick up some coffee in bulgaria through which 
they must travel on their way to turkey 
the goods are sold for a profit back home 
bulgarians whose economy has been sliding into deepening 
crisis face strict food rationing themselves 
in august bulgaria said romanians could travel within bulgaria 
only on organized tours or in transit to another point authorities 
cited a cholera epidemic in romania but many romanians believe the 
reason behind the clampdown was to stop illegal crossborder trade 
the state bulgarian news agency bta charged that in russe 
the romanians swear they are transit travelers however having 
struck quick bargains on the bulgarian black market they go back 
explaining their cars broke down 
in a recent televised speech romanian president ion iliescu 
attacked speculators who think the free market is a way to 
get rich quickly 
growing romanianbulgarian antipathy got a further boost when 
romanian television showed footage of bulgarian militiamen at the 
russe station beating romanians who didnt have correct papers and 
forcing them back across the border 
since summer lines at romanian customs have been growing and 
relations with sofia have started to strain 
seething soviet truck drivers now jockey daily with turkish 
emigrant workers and romanian unofficial traders for a place on the 
rickety 1mile bridge over the danube river 
experienced travelers arrive prepared with food drink and extra 
gasoline for the crossing 
at the giurgiu customs post recently a handful of officials 
no more than in the days of former dictator nicolae ceauscescu 
deliberately search every car and often confiscate hidden taxable 
goods 
smugglers offer cigarettes and whisky as bribes 
fights break out occasionally in the midday heat as drivers 
squabble about who should go first the lines trail back miles over 
the bridge and spew into the opposite lanes blocking the way to 
bulgaria 
bucharest officials say there are no plans to widen the 
40yearold bridge or add lanes to the customs crossing 
