<TEXT>
south african president f w de klerk says 
the new system he envisions for his country will ensure that no 
racial group black or white will ever be able to achieve 
political domination again 
speaking to reporters hours before ending his official visit 
tuesday de klerk ruled out a winnertakeall electoral 
approach in which broad powers are granted to one person 
never again he said should there be a situation in which a 
powerful executive regardless of color is in a strong position 
to suppress south africans of different races 
de klerk said he foresees a new system in which there will be a 
sharing of power within the executive branch thus guarding against 
any concentration of authority 
during his threeday visit the first by a south african head of 
state since 1945 de klerk relentlessly sought to convince doubters 
in the united states that his country is embarking on a new era of 
democracy and racial equality 
i want to say here today that the time has come to realize 
that apartheid is really something of the past he said at a 
national press club luncheon 
as proof he said more than 100 discriminatory laws and 
regulations have been removed from the statute books he promised 
that the remaining impediments will be erased by the time a new 
constitution takes effect 
de klerk also said he was determined to avoid the chaos that has 
prevailed in many other african countries in the postindependence 
era 
we intend to ensure that our plan will absolutely and 
effectively prevent south africa from becoming just another typical 
african oneparty state sliding down the scale of poverty into 
oblivion he said 
we intend to ensure that the new south africa will be based on 
the very values which we share with you 
de klerk said the issue of us sanctions against south africa 
were discussed only indirectly in his talks with president bush 
secretary of state james a baker iii and congressional leaders 
i did not put forward any specific requests he said the 
sanctions among other things bar new us investment in south 
africa and forbid south african aircraft from landing in the united 
states 
rep william gray dpa the house majority whip and 
topranking black in congress said he came away hopeful from 
de klerks session with congressional leaders 
gray said he told de klerk that congress will not be ready to 
ease sanctions until south africa writes a new constitution 
removing the legal pillars of apartheid 
apartheid is alive and well and a reality and until there is a 
new constitution there will be no significant change in that 
society gray said 
asked about the impact of the sanctions de klerk said to a 
great extent it was counterproductive people under threat tend to 
react negatively we dont like as a country to be prescribed to by 
other countries and theres an emotional reaction which is brought 
about by that 
he said south africa began moving toward abandoning its 
apartheid system not because of the sanctions but because we 
believed it must be done 
we are going to do it whether the legislation was instituted 
or not we would have done it according to the policies which we 
have accepted he said 
de klerk has moved partway toward creating conditions that would 
permit the lifting of sanctions through a series of measures 
these include freeing african national congress leader nelson 
mandela and other political prisoners ending the state of 
emergency in all but one province lifting bans on democratic 
political parties and agreeing to negotiate a new democratic 
system 
