<TEXT>
sleep disorders affect millions of americans 
often causing accidents and ruining careers but they usually are 
ignored by physicians and victims may go years without treatment 
in a hearing on capitol hill of the national commission on sleep 
disorders research victims and experts said tuesday that more 
attention must be paid to the suite of sleep ailments that can 
cripple lives end marriages disrupt careers and even cause death 
the need for sleep research is virtually ignored said 
william c dement chairman of the commission and a medical 
professor at stanford university the house of research does not 
have a bedroom 
sleep disorders range from an irresistible urge to sleep an 
ailment called narcolepsy to insomnia which is the inability to 
achieve adequate or restful sleep other problems include 
restless leg syndrome the jerking and twitching of the lower 
limbs during sleep snoring which may be habitual for almost half 
of all adults and sleep apnea a disorder in which breathing stops 
and restarts through the night disturbing rest and perhaps causing 
death in some victims 
people also suffer from sleep disorders caused by travel and 
work schedules that disturb the natural restwake cycle sleep 
cycle changes may pose a particular hazard in modern society the 
experts said 
david dinges a university of pennsylvania psychologist said 
that poor sleep and the resulting lack of alertness is becoming a 
major element in industrial accidents particularly for shift 
workers jet travelers who cross many time zones and those working 
too many hours 
inadequate sleep is a major cause of human error and at least 
as important as drugs alcohol and equipment failure in workplace 
accidents he said 
dinges said airplanes ships factories and power plants all are 
becoming increasingly automated which means humans must sit and 
alertly monitor what the machines are doing 
thats a task we do poorly after missing some sleep 
especially if we have to work at night he said 
dinges said industry and the military are beginning to recognize 
the need to shift work hours to allow for the human need to adjust 
sleep cycles to new schedules 
he said that the use of bright lights to readjust sleep cycles 
shows promise allowing pilots to nap in the cockpit has been 
shown useful in keeping them alert during long transoceanic 
flights he said but other proposed treatments such as special 
diets have proven useless in treating the fatigue of jet lag and 
night shift work 
sufferers of narcolepsy testified that they must constantly 
fight the tendency to suddenly drop off to sleep often at the very 
worst of times 
lori highland of ashford wash said she has spent her life 
in a haze of sleepiness 
my life is haunted by this she said i cant drive i 
have been hospitalized repeatedly for injuries that occur when 
she collapses suddenly into sleep 
mrs highland said that powerful emotions such as anger 
laughter or fear will bring on cataplexy a sudden muscle weakness 
that causes a victim to collapse and be unable to move 
she said that her grandfather had similar symptoms as did her 
mother and now her young daughter 
this has affected four generations said mrs highland my 
mother was labeled a neer do well because she couldnt stay 
awake long enough to do her housework 
she said doctors could not identify her problem for years and 
that she tried many different treatments all unsuccessful mrs 
highland said she was being prepared for surgery to search for 
what was thought to be a brain tumor when a doctor who had taken a 
recent seminar on sleep disorders diagnosed her disorder 
allen music of silver spring md said he suffers from sleep 
apnea which destroys normal sleep and keeps him in a state of 
uncontrolled drowsiness 
before his illness was diagnosed music said he routinely drove 
a car and often would awaken to find the vehicle wrecked because he 
had fallen asleep at the wheel to make even a short trip music 
said he learned that he had to take a nap before he left stop en 
route and nap and then nap when he arrived 
gerald schefey a former methodist minister now in his 50s said 
he had to retire on disability because sleep apnea pushed him to 
the point that he was falling asleep while counseling parishioners 
or while driving 
apnea is not considered a disabling disorder but it is he 
said 
dement and other experts said the causes of narcolepsy are not 
known and there is virtually no treatment for the ailment few 
patients respond to drugs they said 
sleep apnea is now treated with surgery which works about half 
the time and with a sleep mask that feeds oxygen at a pressure 
that keeps airways from sagging closed said dr philip smith of 
johns hopkins university in baltimore 
</TEXT>
