<TEXT>
for years the world bank group has been the 
major source of loans and expertise to stimulate economic 
development in poor mostly tropical countries of asia africa and 
latin america 
now the bank and the related international monetary fund find 
themselves at the center of the action in a cooler part of the 
world nations of the former soviet bloc in central and eastern 
europe 
we are bringing to europe what we have been doing in africa 
the caribbean and so forth said douglas gustafson director of 
investments for europe and the middle east of the groups private 
sector branch the international finance corp 
currently the spotlight is on privatization of largescale 
government enterprise something gustavson described as totally 
uncharted territory 
dramatizing the changes czechoslovakia one of the 22 founding 
countries of the world bank group at bretton woods nh at the 
end of world war ii rejoined last week 36 years after its exit 
was forced by the communist takeover 
prague seeks credits to support drastic price and currency 
reforms planned for the end of 1990 and technical assistance for 
plans to privatize about 70 percent of its statecontrolled 
industry it will use such techniques as distribution of shares to 
the public and perhaps an ifcdesigned mutual fund 
depending on the strength and quality of its reforms newly 
democratic czechoslovakia could draw 300 million to 500 million a 
year of the 11 billion the world bank may lend central and eastern 
european countries in the coming three years said bank department 
director eugenio f lari 
the world bank anticipates lending poland about 800 million a 
year hungary about 400 million and yugoslavia 600 million to 
700 million lari told reporters 
hungary in the forefront of economic reform has been allocated 
23 billion and poland 1 billion worth of world bank credit since 
becoming bank members in 1982 and 1986 respectively they also 
have received assistance in such matters as organizing stock 
exchanges and modernizing banking 
postcommunist bulgaria becomes the 153rd world bank member on 
tuesday 
