<TEXT>
harsher penalties should be levied against 
employers who discriminate against foreignlooking workers to avoid 
hiring illegal aliens according to an administration task force 
the 1986 immigration reform and control act was not intended 
to be a barrier for persons who are eligible to work but the 
evidence shows that many employers are discriminating by adopting 
exclusionary hiring practices the task force said tuesday in its 
report to congress 
those practices include hiring only applicants who prove they 
were born on us soil and rejecting legal immigrants who present 
workauthorization documents issued by the immigration and 
naturalization service the study said 
the task force said fines for discriminating against 
foreignlooking workers should be commensurate with the penalties 
for employers who knowingly hire illegal aliens that would 
increase the maximum fine for repeated discrimination from 2000 
to 10000 it said 
the task force also recommended streamlining the procedures for 
employers to check documents that applicants present to prove 
citizenship or legal status 
