<TEXT>
its that time of fiscal year again the 
government poised for paralysis and the autumnal sky ready to crash 
down on the nations unsuspecting citizens 
the stage is set as usual for 11thhour budget chaos but this 
round is a little different many federal programs may actually be 
cut by nearly onethird 
the public doesnt have the slightest idea of whats coming 
were talking about a serious disruption in government service 
said stan collender director of federal budget policy for the 
price waterhouse accounting firm 
forget eyeglazing phrases like deficit reduction budget 
negotiations and grammrudman sequesters if congress and president 
bush dont agree on tax hikes and spending cuts by monday the 
government shrinks drastically and instantly 
for anyone who thinks thats a great idea here are a few things 
to consider 
the federal aviation administration would have to reduce from 
40000 to 34000 the flights handled by 41 major airports and close 
down 250 weather stations at night forcing cancellation of night 
flights 
the agriculture department would have to lower subsidies for 
major commodities lay off chicken inspectors and close for two 
days a week the local offices where needy farmers get housing and 
operating loans 
the department of health and human services would have to cut 
medicare payments by 2 percent medicare and social security checks 
would be delayed due to personnel cuts 
the bureau of prisons would have difficulty running federal 
prisons on a reduced staff the marshals service wouldnt be able 
to chase as many fugitives or seize as many criminal assets 
few budgetwatchers expect draconian cuts to last long if they 
materialize at all the white house is hoping the mere threat of 
such a cataclysm technically known as a sequester will force an 
agreement sooner rather than later 
but the choices are not pretty particularly for those lawmakers 
facing the voters in five weeks they can support a budget 
agreement that doubtless will raise taxes and reduce services they 
can resist compromise triggering the drastic spending cuts or 
they can extend the deadline for the automatic cuts admitting 
failure and postponing the inevitable moment of truth 
any decision is politically painful even doing nothing 
said collender 
this would not be the first time a budget impasse dragged beyond 
the start of a fiscal year triggering automatic cuts under the 
1985 grammrudman law but the scale this year is something 
entirely new 
in 1986 there was an 117 billion cut when negotiators could 
not agree on a budget by the start of the fiscal year in 1987 the 
slashes otaled 23 billion but they were repealed after a couple 
of months last year after a partial repeal the cuts amounted to 
162 billion now were up to 85 billion to start with more to 
come in midoctober 
were not talking about a flesh wound as we have in the past 
were talking about traumatic injury to vital organs here said 
