<TEXT>
the 108yearold evening express will 
close in february the publisher said 
the merger with the morning portland press herald will take 
effect feb 4 said the guy gannett publishing co 
while were very proud of the evening express changing 
lifestyles have for the past decade caused an increased 
readership of morning newspapers and a corresponding decrease of 
evening circulation said jean gannett hawley publisher of the 
portland press herald and the evening express 
the merger of our two daily newspapers will result in the 
creation of a single paper with more resources and standards of 
quality journalism for mainers hawley said in a statement 
tuesday 
the express had been losing circulation steadily since the early 
1980s its daily circulation now stands at between 22000 and 
23000 
the closing will leave maine with only two afternoon dailies 
the journal tribune in biddeford and the times record in brunswick 
both of which compete with the press herald for readers 
the new press herald will continue to publish monday through 
saturday mornings and include many of the features now contained in 
the evening express along with additional local news the company 
also publishes the maine sunday telegram 
the merger will leave the company with 30 fewer positions but 
the company said it might not have to lay off any employees because 
it had held open vacancies this year and is providing an early 
retirement incentive package 
by taking this action we believe we will be a better 
newspaper for our readers who will get more features and local news 
and our advertisers for whom our circulation will be 
unduplicated steve braver the companys general manager said 
in a statement to employees 
when founded in 1882 by pembroke native arthur wood laughlin 
the express was one of four portland dailies and billed itself as 
the only onecent paper in the state 
five years later the express was taken over by a company headed 
by col frederick neal dow son of staunch prohibitionist neal dow 
whose views were reflected in the newspaper 
dow acquired a competing afternoon paper the daily advertiser 
in 1910 and merged it with the express which by then had the 
largest circulation in the city 
in the 1920s guy p gannett acquired and consolidated the 
citys major daily and sunday papers turning them into the crown 
jewel of a media empire that now includes dailies in waterville and 
augusta a chain of weeklies in minnesota and television and radio 
stations 
after forming the press herald out of the daily press and the 
successor to the old eastern argus gannett bought the express from 
the dow family in 1925 
the express circulation peaked at about 31000 in the late 
1970s 
the closing of the express reflects an industry trend toward 
declining circulation among many afternoon dailies across the 
country that have been struggling in a time of changing lifestyles 
and growing competition from television news 
</TEXT>
