a nationwide program to recognize outstanding 
farm conservationists was announced wednesday by agriculture 
secretary clayton yeutter 
the new take pride in america farm conservation program will 
honor an outstanding farmer in each of nearly 3000 soil and water 
conservation districts during a threeyear period 
yeutter made the announcement in amana iowa where he appeared 
with officials of goodyear tire and rubber the national 
association of conservation districts and the national association 
of state conservation agencies cosponsors of the awards program 
the agriculture department also will step up efforts to improve 
the nations water quality he said 
an objective will be to reduce the risk of agricultural chemical 
pollution of ground and surface water yeutter said in prepared 
remarks released here 
the program was described by yeutter as designed to improve 
coordination among usdas broad array of water quality programs 
and encourage voluntary adoption of agricultural practices to 
improve and protect water supplies 
as part of the plan yeutter said the department will put soil 
conservation service and extension employees from all county 
offices through an intensive training course in methods of 
preserving water quality 
also he said many usda field guides are being rewritten to 
help farmers keep agricultural chemicals out of the water 
