<TEXT>
children are dying from abuse neglect and 
disease at a rate of 40000 a day worldwide the head of the un 
childrens fund said wednesday in a bid to raise awareness of the 
plight of the young 
this weekend president bush and about 70 other heads of state 
or government will gather for a summit at un headquarters to 
adopt a declaration placing children foremost among their national 
priorities 
james grant head of the un childrens fund said the 
declaration will be seen as marking a historic transformation in 
the way the world deals with the children 
we have always in all our religions and cultures given 
children a first call on the resources of the family grant said 
but what is happening now is an extension of this concept to the 
responsibilities of the nationstate to support the family 
the un general assembly adopted the convention on the rights 
of the child last november 
grant said that as of wednesday 43 nations had signed and then 
ratified the convention ratifying nations must guarantee the 
survival of children their protection and development 
more than 100 countries have signed on indicating their 
intention to have their legislatures ratify the convention grant 
said 
the united states has done neither conservatives in congress 
have criticized the convention because it forbids the death penalty 
for people younger than 18 and because it does not define a fetus 
as a child and thus give it special protections 
world leaders will meet sunday to debate the needs of children 
then adopt the declaration and an accompanying action plan 
the plan calls for a onethird reduction in infant mortality by 
the end of the decade access for all couples to family planning 
information and services prenatal care for all pregnant women 
reduction in the rate of low birth weight to below 10 percent a 95 
percent reduction in measles deaths and immunization of 90 percent 
of young children against childhood diseases 
grant said 40000 children die every day twothirds of them 
from largely preventable causes such as from not being vaccinated 
against six killer diseases or the dehydration from diarrhea for 
which we now have a lowcost remedy 
the six deadly childhood diseases are diarrheal disease 
malaria tetanus whooping cough measles and respiratory 
infections 
the other third of the deaths are caused by neglect abuse war 
poverty starvation and diseases for which there is no known cure 
such as aids 
in 1988 250000 civilians died in southern sudan because of 
civil war with the great majority of those being children grant 
said civil conflict the problems in the frontline states like 
mozambique and angola all of these contribute 
but whats clear is that twothirds of the child deaths we 
have today are from readily preventable causes 
