a nasa investigative team has 
identified 83 potential sources of columbias dangerous hydrogen 
leaks and exhaustive testing is expected to pinpoint the problem 
the space agency said wednesday 
the list of suspect parts was narrowed to 83 during an analysis 
of columbias engine compartment said william lenoir head of 
nasas space flight program 
hydrogen flooded the section during fueling last week thwarting 
nasas fourth attempt to send the shuttle on an astronomy mission 
any combination might actually be the culprit lenoir said 
workers will remove insulation from each suspected part and then 
flush helium through the system lenoir said if no leaks are 
found the process will be repeated with a different crew and 
equipment to try to be absolutely sure we havent missed 
anything he said 
if helium does escape the test will be repeated in an attempt 
to really understand what thats telling me at that joint so i 
can maybe make some correlations for the future lenoir said 
so far columbias leaks have appeared only when the shuttles 
external tank is filled with highly flammable liquid hydrogen at 
supercold temperatures which might cause shrinkage of a metal 
part and form the leak the nonflammable helium normally used in 
testing is room temperature 
we know from our previous experience that our helium test has 
not found some of these leaks we thought it should have and we 
want to know why lenoir said 
