one of the first nurses in the nation to 
contract the aids virus from a patient revealed her identity 
wednesday saying she wants to remind all health care workers how 
important it is to take precautions 
if this can happen to me in a small rural hospital in the 
midwest in the middle of the night in 1986 it can certainly happen 
to anybody in 1990 barb fassbinder told reporters 
also wednesday a weekly newspaper in monona a small town in 
northeastern iowa published a letter from the former nurse 
explaining how she contracted the human immunodeficiency virus 
we want to emphasize that i do not have the fullblown disease 
of aids but do have a few relatively minor health problems as a 
result of the infection of the hiv virus she said in her letter 
to the monona billboard 
ms fassbinder 36 stopped working at the hospital in february 
1989 because of health problems and now gets workers compensation 
benefits to pay for medical care the hospital also made a 
settlement agreement that remains confidential the familys lawyer 
said 
the mother of three told reporters she believes she contracted 
the virus in august 1986 during an unsuccessful attempt to 
resuscitate a patient at memorial hospital in prairie du chien 
wis 
she said a doctor told her to remove an intravenous tube from 
the patients arm that wasnt functioning properly she said she 
applied pressure for 10 minutes with her left index finger shielded 
only by a small piece of gauze all that was in reach 
she said the patients blood apparently mingled with her own 
through some small cuts she got while gardening 
it wasnt until december 1986 when she made a routine blood 
donation that the virus was detected ms fassbinder wasnt 
notified of the results until january 1987 
the case was one of the first three documented instances in the 
united states of such infection of a health care worker the 
national centers for disease control cited it as an example of why 
health workers must take precautions against being infected 
ms fassbinder said the burden of living with the secret had 
become too much and that she hoped some good could be accomplished 
by talking openly about aids and hiv infection 
we also need to emphasize that the hiv virus is very fragile 
outside the human body and can only be transmitted in a few very 
specific ways none of which includes social or casual contact or 
even living in the same household she said 
she added that her husband dave 43 and her children eva 13 
joel 10 and emily 7 are infectionfree 
