proposals to require food manufacturers to 
disclose the nutrition content of their products should be extended 
to restaurants a committee of experts recommended wednesday 
the institute of medicine panel also said nutrition labeling 
also should be required for fresh and frozen meat and poultry 
foodlabeling proposals on capitol hill and by the food and drug 
administration already include many of the provisions the panel 
recommended for packaged food seafood and produce 
but neither the pending legislation nor the draft regulations 
addresses meat poultry or restaurants 
the institute is an affiliate of the national academy of 
sciences the congressionally chartered private body established to 
provide scientific advice to government agencies 
the national restaurant association quickly registered its 
opposition to the committees recommendations saying most 
fastfood and fullservice restaurants already provide nutrition 
information voluntarily 
as restaurant operators we firmly believe our customers have a 
right to know what nutrients are in the foods they eat said 
association president mike hurst our concern is not with 
providing such information rather it is with how the information 
is conveyed 
officials at the department of agriculture which regulates meat 
and poultry had said they were waiting for the report before 
making any labeling proposals 
jim greene a spokesman for the departments food safety and 
inspection service said officials had not yet read the report but 
we plan to evaluate the specifics and plan what course to take in 
the near future 
at the food and drug administration spokesman jeff nesbit said 
the agency planned to consider nutritioncontent disclosure for 
restaurants some time in the future but grocery stores are our 
higher priority 
the fda part of the department of health and human services 
last july proposed regulations that would require nutrition 
labeling for nearly all packaged foods and fresh produce and 
seafood 
under its proposal labels would have to show the number of 
calories from fat the amount of saturated fatty acids cholesterol 
and total dietary fiber listing of some vitamins would become 
optional and serving sizes would be standardized 
currently about 60 percent of supermarket foods have nutrition 
information of the label much of that done voluntarily labeling 
is not required except when a manufacturer makes a nutrition claim 
or adds nutrients 
the institutes committee noted that americans spend about 43 
percent of their food money on meals eaten outside the home this 
is expected to amount to about 156 billion this year 
the experts applauded the efforts of some restaurants and 
fastfood chains that have begun providing nutrition information 
voluntarily but they said these efforts should be required by law 
all restaurants serving standardized menu items should be 
required to provide easy consumer access to nutrition profiles of 
standard menu items either by posting the information or printing 
it on containers said richard a merrill committee chairman and 
a law professor at the university of virginia 
other restaurants should have nutrition information for items on 
their menus available for consumers on request he said 
hurst said a national restaurant association survey last year 
showed that threequarters of the 39000 restaurants polled offer 
nutritional information to patrons who request it 
the institutes recommendation would be impractical and 
ineffective hurst said 
printing nutritional information on containers would be 
expensive and burdensome for fastfood restaurants because many of 
their containers are multipurpose he said 
requiring fullservice restaurants to have nutritional 
information on hand would also be costly and timeconsuming 
especially for establishments that change menus daily he said 
