<TEXT>
president bush may rely on an untested legal 
theory to decide which federal programs should be cut sharply next 
week in case no deficitreduction agreement is reached 
administration aides said wednesday 
one official acknowledged that the administration is concerned 
about invoking such authority because congress is jealous of its 
constitutionally protected role as guardian of the federal purse 
strings 
this official reasoned that any shortterm political gain from 
bypassing congress on the spending cuts might be outweighed by a 
resulting deterioration of relations between the two branches 
however some legal scholars say that if the president is 
looking for a way to force spending reductions he might find 
authority in two 1980 advisory opinions by benjamin civiletti 
attorney general near the end of the carter administration 
the essence of civilettis opinions was that a president has 
inherent authority to protect human life and property even when 
congress has not appropriated money for such purposes 
john sununu bushs chief of staff and richard g darman 
director of the white house office of management and budget told 
senate republicans on tuesday that the civiletti option is under 
active consideration 
the maneuver could be used as early as monday that is oct 1 
the first day of the 1991 budget year and congress has yet to 
enact any of the required 13 annual appropriation bills 
a continuing resolution which would keep federal spending 
flowing until oct 20 is making its way through congress bush 
however has promised a veto because one section of the resolution 
would delay 85 billion of mandatory spending reductions called a 
sequester also until oct 20 
bush says that delaying those cuts would reduce pressure to 
write a package of spending reductions and tax increases that would 
slash the deficit by 500 billion over five years he indicated he 
will accept no delays in the arbitrary cuts until a deficit 
agreement is imminent 
if by monday morning bush has refused to sign the continuing 
resolution there will be no money to run most federal programs 
nor will there be any money to sequester 
that is when the civiletti option might be used 
the president invoking his authority to protect human life 
and property could decide that defense department workers should 
come to work and that the justice department should stay home 
foreignaid spending could be frozen national parks could be shut 
down and egg inspectors could be furloughed but the internal 
revenue service could be ordered to keep collecting taxes 
thus the president would have spent federal funds despite the 
constitutional requirement that any spending be approved by 
congress 
this is an area in which there are no cases alan feld a 
boston university school of law professor who has written on the 
civiletti opinion and the federal antideficiency law in which it 
is rooted said in an interview 
all weve got is the bare statute feld said the attorney 
generals opinion is the most authoritative construction of that at 
this moment but it could be wrong it is just the advice the 
president is getting 
aides to some republican senators said there was considerable 
concern among republicans about the presidents acting in such a 
fashion even though they were reluctant to criticize the proposal 
while a deficit agreement was being negotiated 
