<TEXT>
the house voted wednesday to strengthen 
coastal states power over offshore oil drilling 
the bill approved 39132 would overturn a 1984 supreme court 
decision that allowed the federal government to sell offshore oil 
leases without checking to see if drilling complied with states 
plans for its coast 
back in 1972 we made a bargain with the states said rep 
walter jones dnc chairman of the merchant marine and fisheries 
committee who sponsored the bill a revision of the coastal zone 
management act 
if they developed coastal zone management programs which met 
federal standards and received federal approval we promised that 
federal agencies would adhere to these programs 
the problem is that federal agencies have not lived up to this 
bargain 
the supreme court decision stemmed from a lawsuit filed by the 
interior department under president reagan against california for 
trying to stop oil drilling 
the justices ruled that lease sales for drilling on the outer 
continental shelf did not directly affect the coastal zone and 
therefore was exempt from californias management program 
the decision has led to other uses of coastal areas by federal 
agencies that sometimes oppose states management programs said 
jones office 
jones bill establishes a new rule that says any federal 
activity including offshore oil and gas leasing which affects 
any natural resources land uses or water uses in a coastal zone 
would be subject to state review 
the bill says that if the state finds the federal activity to be 
inconsistent with its plan it may ask a federal court to halt the 
activity 
a similar bill is awaiting floor action in the senate however 
the bush administration opposes overturning the 1984 supreme court 
decision and has threatened to veto the legislation 
the coastal management program includes the us territories and 
states on the oceans and the great lakes it is voluntary however 
and five states indiana georgia minnesota illinois and texas 
do not participate 
nonparticipation means the states do not get federal grants 
associated with the program or protection from offshore oil 
drilling if this version of the bill becomes law 
jones bill also requires states participating in the management 
program to develop a water quality strategy to clean up and prevent 
further pollution of coastal waters 
increasingly our nations population is concentrated along 
the coast said jones during debate on the bill i dont need 
to remind my colleagues of the environmental problems which we are 
facing because of this growth 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

