<TEXT>
jesse jackson said wednesday that he is an 
honorable taxpayer and that he will file a district of columbia 
tax return for 1989 even though it may not be legally required 
jackson who is running for the symbolic job of shadow 
senator from the district a post for lobbying congress for dc 
statehood said he has instructed his accountant to file with the 
city a partyear tax form for last year 
jacksons decision came after the washington times reported 
wednesday that the twotime democratic presidential hopeful did not 
file a local tax return last year even though he moved his family 
to the nations capital and registered to vote here in august 
1989 
city tax officials said that even if jackson had filed the form 
he likely would be entitled to a tax credit and would not owe the 
city any money both jackson and a city official agreed that the 
law governing his filing requirement is murky 
we discussed the matter further with local tax experts they 
suggested that the law is vague jacksons office said in a 
statement if through a difference in interpretation he has 
failed to meet a technical requirement in the district that 
requirement will be met immediately by filing a 1989 partyear dc 
tax form 
jacksons accountant lester mckeever of chicago originally 
determined that jackson was not obligated to file a district 
return 
edward many acting associate director for audit compliance and 
investigation for the citys finance and revenue department said 
that residents who move to the district are required to file a tax 
form for that year only if they live in washington for at least 183 
days of the year 
jacksons office said his move to washington was made official 
on aug 3 when he switched his voting registration from chicago 
on that date there were 151 days left in the year 
but another part of the city tax code stipulates that if the 
person is permanently moving to the district he must file the 
partyear form for that year regardless of when the move takes 
place 
in the statement jackson identified himself as a permanent 
resident 
</TEXT>
