<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration concerned 
about signs of poor performance in recent air disasters is 
encouraging changes in flight training to prompt flight crew 
members to work as a team the agency said wednesday 
when it first proposed the change early last year the faa cited 
studies showing that more than 60 percent of fatal airline 
accidents were caused by breakdowns of communication in the cockpit 
rather than mechanical failures or lack of pilot skills 
the faa said then it was clear that in many cases flight crews 
did not work well together and therefore did not make use of all 
the resources at hand during a crisis 
the new faa rule allows airlines the option that airlines use 
cockpit resource management training to emphasize crew 
coordination 
according to the faa such advanced training focuses on 
communications skills coordination and decisionmaking 
this is a bold new approach to the training of flight crew 
members that is sorely needed and one which i believe will enhance 
safety and improve cockpit efficiency said faa administrator 
james b busey 
</TEXT>
