<TEXT>
while new yorks famous carnegie hall 
celebrates its 100th birthday its littleknown counterpart in 
southern west virginia is patching a leaky roof and trying to start 
its own musical renaissance 
i think that carnegie hall has great potential as not only a 
cultural but also as an economic factor said its executive 
director vivian conly 
the greenbrier county building bearing steel baron and 
philanthropist andrew carnegies name was built in 1902 as part of 
a womens college the lewisburg female institute conly said 
carnegie donated 33000 to james lang an institute trustee 
when several buildings on the campus were destroyed by fire lang 
and carnegie were from the same area of scotland according to hall 
records 
the donation was used to build a 500seat theater and performing 
arts center the greek revivalstyle building is across the street 
from a colonial church in this town of 3600 site of a major civil 
war battle 
the hall lay dormant for many years after the womens college 
closed in 1972 and was sold to a state mental hospital the 
building was condemned in 1983 but a citizens group raised the 
money to turn it into a performing arts center 
the center with 450 member families is operated by a staff of 
four with a budget of 214000 said conly who became executive 
director last year 
she said she quit her job as advertising director of the 
greenbrier resort to take on a new challenge the halls 
attempted comeback 
the venue has won praise from performers and patrons for its 
intimate setting 
its a wonderful place to see people because you can see the 
expressions on their faces conly said 
the halls performances once were primarily classical but now 
include gospel jazz bluegrass and folk music artistic programs 
director mary leb said wednesday 
the vienna boys choir the west virginia sympony and taj mahal 
have all performed there 
a local theater group performed steel magnolias a few months 
ago and another play is tentatively lined up for next year 
but the fourstory brick building is in need of extensive 
refurbishing including a new roof new lighting electrical wiring 
and plumbing conly said 
some 125000 has been raised toward a 150000 roofrepair 
project 
fundraisers also hope to bring in revenue from fall classes 
taught in the buildings art studios and classrooms subjects 
include painting sculpture gardening calligraphy and french 
for many reasons it wasnt closely maintained over the 
years conly said it needs a tremendous amount of 
restoration 
