<TEXT>
a federal jury on wednesday found an 
apartment management company guilty of housing discrimination 
because it refused to rent units for use by recovering drug 
addicts 
the jury found that southern management corp had violated the 
fair housing act by refusing to lease the apartments to a drug 
treatment program operated by fairfax county va and awarded 
36280 in damages 
the civil case is one of the first brought by the justice 
department to enforce a 1988 amendments to the fair housing law 
that bar discrimination against recovering alcoholics or drug 
addicts 
the departments civil rights division has also filed 
discrimination suits against communities for blocking group homes 
for mentally retarded persons 
in the virginia case the government presented evidence that 
southern management refused to rent three apartments to the 
countyrun crossroads drug rehabilitation program because it did 
not want recovering addicts living in the units 
recovering addicts who successfully complete a oneyear 
treatment program move to a group home or apartment for four to six 
