thousands of vietnamese boat people will be 
encouraged to fly home voluntarily or face deportation under a 
major united nations policy switch diplomatic sources said 
wednesday 
they will offer the boat people dignity now or deportation 
later said a western diplomat who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
the diplomat said it would be the first time un officials 
threatened deportation to boat people who often travel in 
overcrowded and unsafe vessels to reach the british colony 
previously un officials did not try to influence boat people 
and only accepted volunteers to return home 
about 54000 boat people remain in hong kong camps with 9000 
classified as refugees for resettlement in the west the other 
45000 are either waiting to be screened for determination of their 
status or have been classified as nonrefugees and set for 
repatriation 
jamshid anvar chief of the un high commissioner for refugees 
for asia and oceania informed diplomats of the new policy sources 
said 
britain vietnam and the united nations signed an agreement last 
week that says that in addition to volunteers boat people who 
did not oppose being sent back to vietnam would also be flown 
home 
an official at the un refugee office in hong kong confirmed 
the meeting took place but declined further comment and said anvar 
was not available 
under the agreement with britain and vietnam the united nations 
agreed to monitor returning boat people to ensure they do not face 
political persecution or unnecessary economic hardship 
anvar told the diplomats britain has given the new agreement 
about three months to succeed 
if it fails britain could begin forcible repatriation of boat 
people in 1991 anvar was quoted as saying 
the colonial government forced 51 boat people home in december 
but suspended the program after international condemnation 
in late july secretary of states james a baker iii told 
southeast asin nations the united states still opposed forced 
repatriation but could accept the new category of those who do 
not object 
so far 4349 vietnamese boat people have returned from hong 
kong under a voluntary repatriation program that began in march 
1989 with un support 
hong kong stopped automatically allowing boat people to stay in 
june 1988 since then more than 49400 have arrived including 
nearly 5000 this year 
