familyplanning assistance which emerged as the latest 
battleground in the political war over abortion 
the bill was already under a veto threat however and the vote 
was one in a series of conflicting and confusing senate actions 
that left the bill facing an uncertain future 
a vote to limit debate fell 10 short of the necessary 60 votes 
diminishing prospects of any further action on the bill itself 
the senate approved by a large margin another amendment tuesday 
evening that would nullify bush administration regulations 
prohibiting the family planning clinics from offering any 
information or counseling involving abortion 
the result was a senate bill that contained provisions pushed by 
both antiabortion and abortionrights forces 
in the house meanwhile a similar version extending the life 
of family planning services provided through title x of the public 
health service act of 1970 was approved by the energy and commerce 
committee without any of the controversial senate provisions on 
abortion the clinics offer family planning and health services to 
the poor 
rep henry waxman dcalif subcommittee chairman and an 
abortionrights advocate said he would push for enactment of a 
bill without the senates abortion provisions as a way to avoid a 
presidential veto 
i think our best chance to reauthorize title x is to send a 
simple continuation of the program waxman said 
the family planning acts authorization expired in 1985 but 
services have been funded by congress each year since then through 
socalled continuing resolutions or catchall spending measures 
sen edward kennedy dmass the bills sponsor said the 
action on parental notification means the senate turns our back 
on millions of teenagers but sen orrin hatch rutah 
suggested democrats had only pushed the bill to force president 
bushs veto and said the services would again be funded regardless 
of the bills outcome 
nobody is going to be denied those funds hatch said 
the senate accepted the parental notification amendment offered 
by sen william armstrong rcolo on a unanimous voice vote after 
narrowly defeating a motion to table or kill the amendment that 
key vote against tabling was 5443 
the requirement for parental notification applies only to 
organizations that receive federal money to provide family planning 
services to the poor in cases where girls under age 18 seek 
abortions 
those organizations are prohibited from using federal money for 
abortions but armstrong said more than 30 perform abortions at the 
same clinic that provides federally supported family planning 
services 
in almost every jurisdiction you have to have the permission 
of your parent to give blood armstrong said but there is 
a surgical procedure for which that is not required and it is 
abortion 
armstrong was thwarted in his first attempt to offer the 
amendment tuesday evening sen edward kennedy dmass used 
parliamentary means to block a direct vote on armstrongs 
amendment but on wednesday armstrong succeeded in attaching his 
language to an unrelated amendment 
there are no funds no funds whatsoever that are involved in 
abortion kennedy said referring to federal money 
the senates vote tuesday night to nullify the administrations 
prohibition on abortion counseling provided abortionrights 
advocates with a surprisingly large 62vote majority 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan an abortion opponent 
voted with abortionrights advocates in support of the amendment 
producing an initial 6335 vote but more than an hour after the 
vote was taken dole asked that his recorded vote be changed to 
no 
dole who arrived late for the vote simply made a mistake said 
his press secretary walt riker 
he just made a mistake when he voted riker said 
doug johnson lobbyist for the antiabortion national right to 
life committee said he had expected to lose by about a 6040 vote 
there were a couple of guys who screwed up and were 
confused johnson said that didnt help having the 
republican leader confused 
