president bush has decided to sell 75 
billion in new weaponry to saudi arabia in immediate response to 
the persian gulf crisis and to ask congress consent for another 
14 billion next year sources said 
the package which was to be submitted formally to congress late 
wednesday or thursday includes m1a tanks tow antitank missiles 
bradley fighting vehicles trucks and armored personnel carriers 
said congressional and administration sources who spoke only on 
condition of anonymity 
also included are patriot antimissile batteries although far 
fewer than the 20 or so originally proposed and some apache 
groundattack helicopters the sources said 
items in the package are those which are either in current us 
stocks can be delivered quickly or must be ordered soon to meet 
saudi defensive requirements in the standoff with iraq the sources 
said 
weapons which will take longer to deliver or which meet future 
saudi force needs such as f15f fighter planes will be in the 
package bush will send to congress in january they said 
the administration split the arms sale into two parts after 
supporters of israel on capitol hill complained that the original 
request for some 21 billion in weaponry was too large and was 
being pushed through too quickly 
rep mel levine dcalif a staunch supporter of israel said 
informal assurances he had received led him to believe the new 
package would pass congressional muster 
this is a significant improvement over the original 21 
billion package proposed by the administration levine said this 
is what should have been proposed in the first place 
levine said lawmakers concerned about israels security support 
bushs military moves to counter iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
but the earlier larger arms sale proposal appeared to be an 
attempt to use the crisis as justification for sending items not 
needed for the crisis levine said 
at the same time the administration has been discussing a new 
package of military aid to israel and senior officials have 
promised to maintain israels qualitative military advantage over 
neighboring states 
israels backers said that they expect little objection in 
congress to the administrations new proposal because of strong 
bipartisan support for president bushs policy in the middle east 
and saudi arabias clear defensive needs 
