<TEXT>
a small group wednesday marked one month of a 
roundtheclock peace vigil and pledged to stay at the city park 
until the persian gulf crisis is peacefully resolved 
the peaceworks park vigil began spontaneously aug 26 when 
activists attending a peaceoriented concert at gas works park 
decided they had to do something about the heightening tensions in 
the middle east 
the group of 20 agreed to keep up the 24hour vigil even if it 
meant sacrificing work and family life and giving up the amenities 
of indoor living 
the reason were still here is that the situation in the gulf 
today is just as bad as what motivated us to start the vigil in the 
first place said joseph mabel one of the spokesmen for the 
group 
the vigilists as they call themselves say the group has 
numbered as high as 240 and as low as two or three at any one time 
participants trade shifts and they say there has always been 
someone present 
the group discussed how to prevent hangerson from diverting the 
purpose of the vigil and how to keep members participating when 
winter weather comes 
visitors to the popular park on seattles lake union pass by a 
makeshift camp with rugs recycling bins bicycles canned foods 
and a small library of peaceoriented books 
the group is united in a call for an end to us military 
involvement in the persian gulf but beyond that statement each 
participant speaks individually 
however most share the belief that the bush administration has 
sent us troops to the region for cheap oil rather than for any 
lofty ideal such as creating a stable world order 
vivian mcpeak compares the us policy to that of a junkie 
ready to fight anyone for his next fix 
added karen hill this is a war of businessmen and bankers 
but businessmen and bankers are never the casualties 
some in the group call themselves pacifists but not john hatch 
who recently left the military after seven years of service 
i personally wouldnt mind if the us cleaned saddam 
husseins clock and got out of there hatch said 
but he said he doesnt believe thats possible and fears the 
united states will become bogged down in a long bloody war 
hatch who decided to quit his job as a janitor to participate 
said the groups number is increasing as passersby learn of the 
vigil and join up 
one of the visitors wednesday was former rep mike lowry 
dwash who lost a senate race after 10 years in congress before 
becoming a seattle university professor of political science 
