epa administrator william reilly called 
wednesday for a reexamination of the nations environmental 
priorities to focus more attention on the areas of greatest risk 
reilly in an address to the national press club said limited 
resources to deal with the vast number of environmental issues 
facing the country must not be wasted on lowpriority items 
he released a report by the agencys science advisory board 
which concluded that too many agency decisions are made because of 
publicily perceived health risks and not risks based on scientific 
research 
the report said among other things that epa should attach as 
much importance to reducing ecological risk as it does to reducing 
human health risk 
the advisers grouped problems into high medium and low risk 
areas 
oill spills groundwater pollution and radioactive isotopes pose 
relatively low risks they said 
pesticides acid rain and surface water pollution were examples 
of what they said were mediumrisk areas 
the highrisk group consisted of four problems global warming 
from the greenhouse effect depletion of the ozone layer loss 
of biological diversity and extinction of species and destruction 
of natural environments such as rain forests 
reilly and his predecessors have expressed chagrin that the 
agency at congressional direction spends billions of dollars 
every year on cleaning up toxic waste dumps which among other 
things pollute groundwater and much less on more serious 
environmental and health risks 
we must do a better job in setting environmental priorities 
said reilly he urged a broad robust national dialogue 
involving the epa congress industry and the public on what areas 
pose the greatest risks and where government resources should be 
directed 
are we spending all our money on the right things reilly 
asked too often in the area of environmental protection the 
government has not he suggested 
as we gear up to deal with the environmental problems of the 
1990s and beyond i think the time has come to start taking aim 
before we open fire he said 
