president bush asked congress on wednesday for 
a streamlined process to negotiate a freetrade agreement with 
mexico the nations thirdlargest trading partner 
the agreement would be aimed at removing tariffs quotas and 
other trade barriers between mexico and the united states a 
freetrade treaty already is in force between the united states and 
canada 
canada also has asked to participate in the us negotiations 
with mexico to achieve a trade treaty applying to all three 
countries bush said the administration would explore the 
possibility of a threenation accord and inform congress of his 
recommendations 
in a letter to the senate finance committee and house ways and 
means committee bush formally notified lawmakers of his intention 
to open trade talks with mexico 
he said that mexican president carlos salinas de gortari has 
undertaken dynamic marketoriented reforms 
we see substantial opportunities for mutual benefit in further 
lowering impediments to bilateral trade in goods and services and 
to investment the president said 
the notification gives congress 60 legislative days to decide 
whether or not to deny bushs request for socalled fasttrack 
negotiating authority because of the congressional calendar the 
60day period should run out sometime next spring 
if the fasttrack process is authorized the united states would 
begin negotiations under rules that would prevent the senate from 
being able to amend any treaty that results 
sen lloyd bentsen dtexas who chairs the finance committee 
signalled a certain reluctance to embrace the fasttrack 
noamendment process 
never before have we negotiated a freetrade agreement with a 
country so different from us economically he said 
bush said that if the united states decides to expand the talks 
with mexico into a threenation negotiating process it would not 
affect the validity of the trade agreement with canada 
last year the united states exported 2497 billion in goods to 
mexico and received 2719 in imports for a deficit of 22 
billion mexico has the worlds eighth largest oil reserves and a 
freetrade pact with the united states could spur oil production 
