carnegie hall opened its centennial season 
wednesday with the same piece of music that opened the very first 
concert in the hall on may 5 1891 
beethovens leonore overture no 3 was performed expertly 
and with restraint by the los angeles philharmonic conducted by 
its former music director andre previn the offstage horn was 
crisp and the flute soloist was excellent 
carnegie hall is celebrating its 100th anniversary for the next 
seven months ending with a may 5 concert by various soloists and 
the new york philharmonic that will fulfilling the wish of 
carnegies executive director judith arron that american orchestras 
open and close the season 
before wednesday nights program began a fanfare brought the 
audience into the hall and the los angeles philharmonic played a 
preconcert starspangled banner in arturo toscaninis 
orchestration 
after the leonore the orchestra played two pieces by 
americans written some half century after carnegie hall opened but 
not avantgarde 
itzhak perlman was soloist in barbers 1939 concerto for 
violin and orchestra hearing this piece melodic and attactive 
to the ear makes one wonder why it isnt programmed more often 
lush violins are saved from sounding like movie music by the good 
taste of the melodies perlmans tone went from silver shimmering 
like leaves in an aspen grove to warmly mellow 
the second movement had an elegant pastoral melody played by 
solo oboe in the pizzicato of the third perlman swung his 
shoulders in time to what he was playing some parts of the third 
movement had fast russian rhythms 
after intermission schumans symphony no 3 from 1941 was 
played when it finished william schuman who was 80 in august and 
has been composing for 50 years took a bow from a box 
coming right after the barber piece which seems to flow 
naturally the symphonys changes of mood seem to lack coherence 
but it gave the brass and percussion their chance during the 
evening to be loud and even for the violins to be robust 
it was a bigfinish halfhour fanfare to carnegie halls 
centennial season 
the audience many of whom had bought 1000 tickets and were 
continuing on to a dinner dance at the metropolitan club gave the 
opening night concert a standing ovation 
