<TEXT>
ron kottemanns days are measured in 
hoofbeats and 12inch lengths of taffy his wages are quarters 
paid out mainly from small sweaty palms his shop is a fourfoot 
by sixfoot swaying box perched on high wooden wheels 
theres no better way to make a living in the world they can 
keep all their desk jobs said the roman candy man 
in the narrow wooden wagon drawn by rosie the mule kottemann 
makes and sells the handpulled italian taffy just as he 
grandfather did while rosie tows him through the streets of new 
orleans he boils up the sweet yellow globs adds vanilla 
strawberry or chocolate then kneads and pulls it into glistening 
sticky rope 
my grandfather started this in those days everybody had a 
wagon it wasnt a big deal youd see all sorts of wagons going 
around town with people selling stuff the world changed but we 
didnt said kottemann 41 
well some changes but only small ones the price has gone up 
roman candy sticks that sold for a nickel when sam cortese started 
making them in 1915 now go for a quarter 
kottemann has also added a second wagon that is permanently 
stationed at the audubon zoo and he sells to about 20 stores 
wholesale 
people tell me i should modernize kottemann said they 
say i should get rid of rosie and the wagon and get a truck but if 
i did that it would become a twoman operation id need someone to 
drive and someone to make the candy this way rosie drives and i 
make the candy she responds to voice commands so i hardly ever 
have to even touch the reins were the perfect team 
kottemann takes rosie from her stable behind his uptown new 
orleans home around 9 am and goes to work 
usually five days sometimes six once in a while seven if i 
need the money i try not to work on sundays and almost never on 
monday thats a real dead day for business he said 
he stops for business in various parts of town each morning 
downtown some days outside the parks on others occasionally in 
the french quarter 
i like to go into the quarter but only if there are a lot of 
local folks there the tourists think the wagon is cute and they 
take a lot of pictures but they dont know what roman candy is and 
they dont usually buy lots of smiling not many sales thats the 
tourist trade for me he said 
he changes locations in the afternoon every day during the 
school year he sets up outside a school before the closing bell 
things started changing about 10 years ago kottemann said 
i used to spend most of the days just driving through different 
neighborhoods it used to be that mama was home with the kids now 
mama and dad are both at work and the kids are in day care i can 
drive through a neighborhood now and not see a soul before 4 or 5 
oclock 
kottemann started working on the roman candy wagon with his 
grandfather when he was in the eighth grade by the time he went to 
college and then to the army he knew he wanted to carry on the 
business 
cortese died in 1969 as kottemann entered the service the 
candy wagon was off the street for three years the only shutdown 
in 75 years when kottemann was discharged the wagon began to make 
its rounds again 
he sells an average of 600 sticks of candy a day and with his 
zoo wagon and his store accounts kottemann said he makes a good 
living for his family it probably wouldnt support a big group 
but its plenty for us 
the future at this point kottemanns not sure 
crime is his biggest concern kottemann said hes not worried 
about his candy wagon being robbed hes afraid it will get so 
dangerous to live in town that he may have to move 
that would really hurt as it is now rosies stable is right 
in the back yard its been there for 100 years i just unhitch 
