in the greatest assemblage of world leaders 
ever gathered the world summit for children meets on sunday 
shadowed by crisis that threatens the peace and peace dividend that 
seemed at hand when it was conceived 
the leaders of more than 70 governments are to sit at one 
gigantic united nations conference table there are places for 74 
to talk about the worlds children their needs and what can be 
done to meet them 
only the heads of governments can participate no standins or 
deputies at the table the summit census nearly doubles what was 
the record 38 world leaders who met at the united nations on its 
40th anniversary in 1985 
president bush will be in new york for the sunday summit and is 
to speak briefly since there are to be about 30 speeches they are 
limited to a maximum of 5 minutes each every orator has been 
forewarned 
these most powerful people in the world are getting together 
to deal with the problems of the most vulnerable people in the 
world said jay ross a spokesman for the united nations 
childrens fund that carries a message 
the statistic cited over and over in preparation for the summit 
every day about 40000 children under age 5 die of starvation or 
diseases that could be prevented 
it is the greatest condemnation of our times that more than a 
quarter of a million small children should still be dying every 
week of easily preventable illness and malnutrition said james 
p grant the unicef executive director in the 1989 annual report 
that gave rise to the summit plan 
indeed until aug 2 it seemed that the 45th general assembly 
of the united nations the first of the postcold war era could 
concentrate on that and other chronic world problems 
then iraq invaded kuwait igniting the first major crisis of the 
new era and the un became the crucial forum in the world 
response to baghdad voting to impose a trade embargo and 
authorizing the use of force if necessary to make it stick 
iraqi diplomats tried futilely to link the embargo with the 
summit on children asserting at one planning session that it would 
lead to starvation of their young and that the summit should say 
so it wont nor will iraq be participating on sunday saddam 
hussein had said he would send his governments health minister 
but aides were not invited to participate only to watch 
there were echoes of other more familiar complaints dating 
from cold war times as summit planners put together a world 
declaration on the survival protection and development of 
children 
the statement due for ceremonial signing by the summit 
participants on sunday lists war aggression and foreign 
occupation among the causes of the suffering of children a cuban 
diplomat proposed amending the statement to include colonialism as 
another cause a british aide said that it should list totalitarian 
dictatorships instead both amendments were scrapped 
with the ebbing of cold war the statement says significant 
resources could be released for purposes other than military 
ones and the needs of children should be a priority claim on 
those resources 
thats the peace dividend argument it runs headon into the 
deficits plaguing the united states and the economic crisis 
wrenching the soviet union 
the summit statement also promises a global attack on 
poverty seeking more aid trade debt relief and economic growth 
for the developing world at this point the industrial nations are 
struggling against an economic slump of their own worsened by the 
sharp increase in oil prices because of the persian gulf crisis 
it urges every nation to reexamine its current national 
budget and its foreign aid commitment to give priority to 
programs to cut child mortality and hunger and to make primary 
education available to at least 80 percent of the worlds children 
by the year 2000 
the summit declaration seeks those goals and more acknowledging 
that they are ambitious and will take extraordinary worldwide 
effort 
in that quest the fact that sundays meeting is being held may 
be more important than anything said there it puts the problems of 
children on a world stage at least for a day 
the challenge now will be to translate one day at the summit 
ino a drive that will last the decade 
 
editors note walter r mears vice president and columnist 
for the associated press has reported on washington and national 
politics for more than 25 years 
