nearly 10 years ago cspan began its first 
callin show alas there was a power failure despite the fact 
that cspan is in washington dc where even reporters think they 
have power 
something went poof and the lights all blew the power blew 
cspan chairman brian lamb recalls repairs were made in five 
minutes but for a while it was bizarre guerilla television 
on oct 7 cspan will celebrate its 10th year of callins with 
the same four guests journalists on the communications beat 
discussing how todays issues in the communications industry 
compared to those of 1980 
back then a viewer from yankton sd was the first caller to 
cspan a nonprofit company originally created by the cable 
television industry to provide gaveltogavel coverage of house 
proceedings 
lamb doesnt recall the first callers name but thats 
understandable he estimates that about 100000 viewers have dialed 
in since then to grill guests or have their say on the hot issues 
of the day 
the callers he does remember range from an 11yearold 
mississippi schoolgirl to gary owens the freespirit announcer 
from the old laughin series to former president reagan who 
has called twice 
the audience and callers cspan currently serves nearly 51 
million homes in the us no longer are only americans that 
changed in 1988 
now its two 90minute weekday callin shows in the morning and 
early evening plus additional ones held after such events as a 
presidential speech are carried via satellite in 26 other 
countries mainly in europe 
viewers there also can phone in although only two lines are set 
up for their calls compared to eight for domestic dialers in all 
cases each dialer foots the cost of the toll call 
the topics discussed usually are national and international 
matters such as the federal budget social security highway 
safety legal issues and in recent weeks the persian gulf crisis 
and the savings and loan mess 
the majority of guests tend to be federal officials and house 
and senate members when he was vice president president bush was 
a guest his vice president dan quayle also has been on fielding 
questions 
it may be heresy but lamb says print journalists not the 
electronic kind are the shows secondlargest group of guests his 
reasoning 
television fills in a blank or two but if you go to the 
backbone of where people get their information its in the 
newspaper 
like their radio cousins television callin shows have become 
so rampant they give common a bad name but cspans are unique in 
two regards 
one is that they have no star hosts the shows never say in 
advance who the hosts will be there are 10 three of them 
journalists the rest including lamb are cspan staffers for whom 
hosting is a secondary job 
on any given day for example the host could be bruce collins 
cspans chief attorney or susan swain its senior vice president 
for programming lamb says 
we want people to tune in for the issues and the guests 
instead of the hosts he says 
as in 1980 all the calls are live there is no sevensecond 
delay a common device of callin shows now to let the host dump 
a dialer who might fancy himself the next andrew dice clay 
weve always tried to make this as real as possible so that 
the audience wont feel any kind of technical interference between 
them and the guests lamb says 
the show does periodically hear from those who are none too 
tightly wrapped he says but that is not the norm by any stretch 
of the imagination but he concedes if the moon is full and 
this is not an exaggeration you can have a very unusual 
program 
it is the nature of life that hosts of television talk shows 
often are guests on other television talk shows phil donahue does 
it all the time 
although lamb is a noname relatively speaking as a callin 
show host he too has been a guest twice on a national 
television callin show larry kings show on the cable news 
network 
each visit induced high anxiety he says its much easier 
being a host than a guest youre in control when youre the host 
when youre the guest youre totally at the mercy of the host 
so i have a great appreciation for how we can screw things 
up 
 
