<TEXT>
the governments factual presentations are grossly distorted 
its discussion of legal principles and applicable law virtually 
nonexistent indeed in its zeal to enhance mr milkens 
punishment the governments sentencing memorandum is inconsistent 
with portions of its own plea agreement and with the 
representations the government made to the court at the time of mr 
milkens plea 
first the governments memorandum confirms that there is 
no evidence linking mr milken in any way to a significant number 
of the alleged acts which the government asks this court to 
consider 
second the government has provided a highly selective 
version of its own evidence on a host of other transactions which 
it urges this court to consider 
the governments sentencing memorandum also seeks to 
punish mr milken for acts which do not constitute crimes it 
even blames mr milken for the fact that in december 1989 one 
year after the government banished mr milken from drexel and 
barred any drexel employee from even talking to him about anything 
directly or indirectly relating to business drexel which was 
then led by john shad the former chairman of the sec paid large 
bonuses to its employees 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
to accept the governments position would subject mr milken to 
punishment on charges that the government had agreed previously to 
dismiss with prejudice and would impose on this court the 
obligation to issue extensive findings of fact and conlusions of 
law on all matters that would have arisen had mr milken actually 
proceeded to trial to attempt to resolve these matters without 
full evidentiary hearings would violate due process but to hold 
such hearings which could last as long as a trial would be 
contrary to sound principles of judicial administration and would 
be inconsistent with the essence of the plea agreement 
the sentencing stage is not the time to conduct new trials 
on new offenses 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
unlike its typical sentencingmemorandum the government here 
does not analyze the relevant sentencing precedents in this 
district the reason is obvious the governments recommendation 
that mr milken receive a substantial period of incarceration 
cannot be reconciled with these precedents 
only three of the nearly 100 securities law violators 
sentenced in this district who pleaded guilty received prison 
sentences greater than one year and one day 
by every relevant indicator mr milken has fully and 
unconditionally accepted complete responsibility for the crimes he 
committed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
we would have expected the government to acknowledge that he was 
no ivan boesky martin siegel dennis levine or even robert 
freeman 
no matter how unjust it must brand mr milken an insider 
trader to justify its own investigation yet its four isolated 
allegations of insider trading are easily refuted by documents and 
testimony currently in the possession of the government 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the government charges that drexel provided unlawful gratuities 
to money managers and other institutional fiduciaries principally 
in the form of lucrative investment opportunities michael 
milkens business was not based on improper inducements to anyone 
the governments theory of wrongdoing presumes a world in 
which no one ever recommends a security to a client or tries to 
make money for a client if the client works for an institutional 
customer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in a balanced sentencing memorandum given the public clamor 
over the savings and loan crisis we would have expected the 
government to disclose forthrightly that it does not contend that 
mr milken was responsible for the financial collapse of any 
savings and loan obviously although the government does not 
publicly exonerate mr milken in its 215page memorandum it makes 
no claim and presents no evidence linking mr milken to todays 
savings and loan crisis 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
to understand the true nature of the transactions between boesky 
and mr milken it is necessary to understand the complex 
relationship between a securities salesman and his or her customer 
scorekeeping by brokers of profits lossses and favors for 
accounts is common in the industry so are efforts to make up 
losses 
the governments principal evidence in support of its 
position are the handwritten ledgers it has attached to its 
sentencing memorandum and boeskys payment of a 53 million fee 
to drexel but a careful review of the ledgers and of their 
origins reveals that far from being the memorialization of a 
boeskymilken illegal arrangement the ledgers were nothing more 
than an artifice used by both sides to gain an advantage through 
scorekeeping 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the governments allegation that michael milken obstructed 
justice is as unfounded as its other allegations to begin with 
much of what the government characterizes as obstruction is not 
obstruction at all during the immediate aftermath of the service 
of grand jury and sec subpoenas at drexel there was unquestionably 
confusion fear and paranoia but confusion fear and paranoia are 
hardly illegal and were surely justifiable under the circumstances 
under these circumstances behavior that might otherwise 
seem silly or even paranoid furtive conversations or warnings 
about who might be an informant are perfectly understandable and 
they are not illegal 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
beyond urging this court to sentence mr milken for additional 
crimes in the absence of factual or legal support the government 
asks the court to punish mr milken for the demise of drexel and 
for his wealth and his status in the community these charges have 
no place at sentencing and do not befit the government 
as a result of drexels collapse in bankruptcy court 
mr milken has personally lost more than any other individual 
investor 
the governments sentencing memorandum includes no fewer 
than 25 references to mr milkens wealth and power in the 
first 25 pages alone just as such appeals to passion or 
prejudice are forbidden at trial they are equally offensive at 
sentencing 
</TEXT>
