<TEXT>
here is a snapshot of michael milken the 
deposed junkbond king who faces sentencing in the largest ever 
securities fraud case against an individual 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
born on the fourth of july in 1946 milken grew up in encino 
calif as a boy he helped his father an accountant prepare tax 
returns for clients milken graduated from the university of 
california at berkeley majoring in business administration and 
married highschool sweetheart lori anne hackel he went on to 
receive a master in business administration degree from the 
university of pennsylvanias wharton school 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
milken was hired fulltime by drexels bondtrading department 
in 1970 after working in its philadelphia office during business 
school a rapid success milken was generating a substantial amount 
of the firms profits through his highyield bond trading in 1978 
the firm allowed milken to move the highyield bond department to 
beverly hills calif drexel used junk bonds to finance hundreds of 
small companies in the 1980s reaping hundreds of millions of 
dollars in fees junk bonds later were used to finance a wave of 
corporate takeovers 
milken used some of his earnings to start charitable foundations 
that he and his brother lowell also a drexel employee endowed 
with hundreds of millions of dollars 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
after being linked in the press in late 1986 to an illegal stock 
trading network led by admitted felon ivan boesky milken and 
drexel became the main targets of the governments insider trading 
probe they were charged with civil fraud and other allegations by 
the securities and exchange commission in 1988 and drexel that 
winter agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay 650 million 
in penalties 
milken his brother and former drexel trader bruce newberg were 
indicted in march 1989 on 98 counts of fraud and racketeering 
related to insider trading and other alleged securities violations 
in a series of takeover deals from 1985 to 1987 milken vowed to 
fight the charges 
milken resigned from drexel in june 1989 and set up a 
consulting and investing firm 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in a reversal milken agreed in april to a plea bargain with 
prosecutors rather than go to trial friends said he saw no end to 
the ordeal otherwise plus the government agreed to drop all 
charges against lowell milken 
on april 24 1990 milken entered guilty pleas to six felonies 
and agreed to pay 600 million in penalties prosecutors said his 
agreement to cooperate with investigators could help in other 
prosecutions 
specifically milken pleaded guilty to conspiracy aiding and 
abetting the filing of a false statement with the sec securities 
fraud aiding and abetting netcapital requirements mail fraud and 
assisting the filing of a false tax return 
i realize that by my acts i have hurt those who are closest to 
me i am truly sorry he said tearfully in court 
sentencing by us district judge kimba wood was set for oct 1 
milken faces a maximum of up to 28 years in prison 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

