<DOCNO> AP900926-0230 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
senate passage of a stock market reform bill 
that expands the securities and exchange commissions powers was 
reached after congressional staffers hammered out a compromise on 
program trading 
the compromise bill passed on a voice vote tuesday will allow 
the sec to regulate the controversial computerdriven trading 
strategy during times of extreme market turbulence known as 
volatility 
volatility frightens away the investors american firms need to 
compete and grow said sen donald riegle jr chairman of the 
senate banking committee which oversees the sec the reforms the 
senate enacted today take aim at excess volatility letting the sec 
stop such practices before they do their damage he added 
the legislation is expected to move to the full house within a 
few days if passed by the house the bill would then go to 
president bush for his signature 
this legislation strengthens the secs oversight of our 
securities markets and the participants in those markets said 
sen christopher dodd dconn one of the bills original 
sponsors 
the bill was worked out between the staffs of the senate banking 
committee and the house energy and commerce committee over the last 
month 
the talks were very cordial said a house committee aide 
in addition to the program trading curb the compromise market 
reform bill contains provisions passed separately by both the house 
and senate 
one expands the authority of the sec chairman to shut down the 
securities markets with presidential permission in times of 
market emergency previously only the president could order a 
trading halt 
other provisions 
require large securities traders to report their market 
positions to the sec 
mandate coordinated clearance and settlement of stocks 
options and futures contracts between the sec and the commodity 
futures trading commission 
require the treasury department federal reserve board the 
cftc and sec to report annually to congress on their efforts to 
protect the integrity of the markets 
give the sec authority to assess the financial health of the 
parent holding companies of brokerdealers 
the collapse of drexel burnham lambert inc the onetime junk 
bond giant of wall street was precipitated in february by the 
failure of its parent holding company which sec officials have 
complained they had no authority to monitor 
sec chairman richard c breeden said he was very pleased with 
the senate passage of the market reform bill and looked forward 
to the continuing congressional process 
the original house version the securities markets reform act 
passed in june contained a provision giving the sec authority to 
limit program trading during periods of extraordinary market 
volatility the sharp climbs or drops in stock prices 
the original senate version the market reform act passed last 
month did not have a program trading provision 
critics of program trading the rapidfire transactions through 
computerized buy and sell programs of enormous blocks of stocks 
blame it for worsening the 1987 stock market crash and the 
190point market drop last oct 13 
they are especially critical of one form of program trading 
index arbitrage in which speculators try to take advantage of 
small brief price differences between the stock and futures 
markets by simultaneously buying large orders in one market while 
selling in the other 
critics say that strategy andthe volatility that often seems to 
accompany it have driven small investors out of the stock market 
but industry groups including the new york stock exchange and 
the securities industry association have said their studies have 
not shown program trading to be the cause of the 1987 crash and 
suggested other ways to control market volatility 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

