<TEXT>
us car and truck makers turned in surprisingly 
strong midseptember sales figures down 56 percent from last 
year leading to speculation among analysts that the mideast crisis 
has yet to affect showroom traffic 
the 10 major us automakers reported tuesday their car and 
truck sales for the sept 1120 period fell to an average daily 
rate of 35810 vehicles compared with a rate of 37948 during the 
same time last year 
a 423 percent increase in the sales of cars by japanese 
companies was offset by a 75 percent decline in cars made by 
general motors corp ford motor co and chrysler corp the big 
three held 857 percent of the car market in midseptember 
on the whole it was a pretty good number said auto analyst 
david healy of barclays de zoete wedd investment bankers in new 
york i didnt expect them to come anywhere close to last year 
car sales were down 26 percent and truck sales were off 105 
percent 
the decline in truck sales led healy to wonder if the effects of 
rising gasoline prices stemming from the iraqs invasion of kuwait 
may begin showing up in dealerships soon 
if cars are down 2 percent and trucks are down 10 percent 
maybe there is a little shying away from gasguzzling trucks he 
said 
analysts speculated the sales rate may have received a jolt from 
wheeling and dealing that goes on in showrooms this time of year as 
dealers switch over from 1990 models to 1991 versions 
last year at this time automakers offered big incentives to 
shrink bloated newvehicle inventories this year inventories are 
lower lessening the need for incentives 
an amazing performance economist tom webb of the national 
automobile dealers association in mclean va said of the 
midseptember sales rate even skittish consumers are finding the 
model year closeout bargains too good to pass up 
