<TEXT>
without a shortterm loan the city of 
philadelphia will be forced to live day to day on cash receipts 
until major property tax payments arrive in late february 
according to a city report 
in an analysis of the citys cash condition the finance 
directors office urged state and local political leaders tuesday 
to back its search for such a loan 
the city would in this event be insolvent the analysis 
said such a condition of insolvency has never happened to a 
major american city 
two of the citys three major taxes property and business 
privilege are due annually in the spring and the city has 
borrowed annually since 1972 to meet payroll and other obligations 
until those funds arrived 
a 375 million note offering was postponed sept 12 because it 
failed to attract investors 
the analysis said the offering was undercut by adverse 
publicity the lack of definitive public commitments at the state 
and local levels to find a permanent correction and the 
corresponding high degree of uncertainty about philadelphias 
fiscal future 
according to the analysis five steps are needed to regain 
access to the markets 
pledges from key state and local leaders to ensure that 
noteholders would be repaid 
clarification from city controller jonathan a saidel of his 
position on the need for seasonal cashflow borrowing 
demonstrated willingness by state and local leaders to find a 
longterm solution to the citys underlying fiscal problems 
at least a minimal commitment from state and local banks to 
back the notes 
action by the state on one of six proposals that would enhance 
the citys financial standing 
the proposals that would need state approval include 
longstanding requests for full state funding of statemandated 
human services programs a significant advance on state funds the 
city already is expected to get this fiscal year or state 
guarantees on the notes 
the other possibilities are passage of mandatory withholding of 
the citys wage tax from the paychecks of an estimated 25000 city 
residents who work in the suburbs passage of a local sales tax and 
approval of deficit financing 
the analysis also outlines various cashsaving steps it can take 
itself without a shortterm note including freezes in hiring 
payments to the city pension fund and repayment of an illegal 
realestate transfer tax 
mayor w wilson goode said last week the city could save 122 
million through such steps delaying until dec 1 the date when it 
would run out of cash 
for a longterm solution to the citys financial ills the 
analysis restated proposals goodes administration has pushed for 
two years 
the main elements still lacking the analysis said are a 
permanent funding source for the regional masstransit system tax 
reform and increased local taxes and additional state aid mostly 
for mandated human services programs 
