<TEXT>
foreign banks have been setting up shop on us 
soil in increasing numbers over the years lending money to 
corporations investing in government securities even accepting 
deposits 
in many cases theyve been competing headon with 
americanowned banks 
now as many us banks retrench abroad and struggle with a 
slumping real estate market at home some critics charge foreign 
institutions are bullying their us counterparts in a financial 
freeforall 
they suggest foreign banks be bound by new controls but others 
say the current opendoor policy best serves the american 
consumers 
buoyed by the equaltreatment policies of the international 
banking act of 1978 overseas bankers have expanded their american 
operations by a startling 2800 percent since the early 1970s they 
rushed in to help finance the federal deficit and make commercial 
loans in a vast diversified market that offered new horizons for 
expansion 
meanwhile american banks reined in their international lending 
as some of their loans soured and capital considerations grew more 
urgent 
the 670 foreignowned bank branches agencies and subsidiaries 
account for nearly 30 percent of all outstanding commercial or 
business lending 
at the end of last year us assets of foreign banks totaled 
7357 billion compared with 261 billion in 1972 according to 
figures provided by the federal reserve about 55 percent of those 
assets are from japanese institutions the fed said 
real estate developer donald trump knows first hand the global 
power and importance of japanese banks he has been forced to knock 
on the doors of several japanese banks during his cash crunches 
this year 
in a recent report the nippon keizai shimbun japans premier 
financial newspaper claimed trump owes a third of his debts to 
japanese banks 
faramarz damanpour author of the recently published book the 
evolution of foreign banking institutions in the united states 
called the growing dependence on foreign banks alarming he 
suggests requiring a certain level of us participation in foreign 
banking operations 
if we do not please the japanese then we are at their 
mercy said damanpour a james madison university professor 
the similarity can be to the opec oil 
robert dugger chief economist of the washingtonbased american 
bankers association says foreign banks often act in concert with 
the fiscal policies of their home countries not those of the 
united states 
as a result they sometimes can draw on extra funds because of 
lower reserve requirements regulatory costs and deposit insurance 
premiums in many foreign lands he said the playing field is 
tipped significantly in their favor 
but lawrence r uhlick executive director of the new yorkbased 
institute of international bankers says foreign banks also have 
guidelines to follow 
he noted that the bank for international settlements which acts 
as a bank for central banks of major industrialized countries 
adopted riskbased capital standards two years ago the swissbased 
bank also set a march 1993 deadline for banks to hold capital equal 
to at least 8 percent of their loans and other assets he said 
uhlick said foreign bnnks provide healthy competition in lending 
and other banking services and additional financing to the us 
market they also boost international trade in part by financing 
us operations of businesses from their home countries he said 
a lot of people look at the size of the us business that has 
been done by banks around the world and they draw from that the 
conclusion that foreign banks are stealing us business somehow 
said james m stewart general manager of den danske bank a danish 
company with offices in new york and los angeles 
really thats not the case whats happening is that banks 
are bringing capital and a capacity to participate in transactions 
that would not otherwise be completed 
any effort to pass protectionist legislation will only backfire 
some say 
other markets may not remain open to american banks if the 
us restricts access of other countries banks to its market 
said uhlick id let the consumer decide how best their financial 
services are going to be met 
some bankers and lawmakers have called for deregulating the 
entire us banking system to unshackle both foreign and american 
institutions to develop a foundation to compete worldwide they 
say us banks must be given freedom to expand easily from state 
to state and to do insurance and securities business that is now 
offlimits to them 
if you cant go where other individuals can go if you cant 
do what other individuals can do that impedes your ability to 
compete said rep john lafalce dbuffalo ny a member of the 
house task force on international competitiveness 
one effort to rework the banking system is embodied in house 
bill 1992 it would allow creation of depository institution 
holding companies that could provide banking securities or 
insurance services though subsidiaries 
while that may help some banking experts say the problems 
facing us banks run much deeper 
we are losing our respect in financial and capital markets 
said damanpour 
he says that in the long term americans must improve their 
educational system rebuild the infrastructure and abandon what he 
views as an outmoded ethos of greed and easy living 
</TEXT>
