<TEXT>
american allies raised new questions today 
concerning a fundraising campaign launched by president bush to 
collect the billions of dollars needed in the persian gulf crisis 
as officials representing more than 20 nations prepared to hold 
an organizational meeting of the gulf crisis financial coordination 
group it was clear that the allies who were expected to put up the 
cash had a number of objections to the outline of the effort 
unveiled by bush on tuesday 
the disputes ranged from such basic issues as how much money 
should be contributed to which countries should receive the 
assistance there were also debates over what mechanisms to use to 
disburse the funds 
treasury secretary nicholas brady expressed the hope today that 
the various questions could be resolved telling global finance 
ministers in a speech that they needed to forge a united economic 
front against saddam hussein 
the economic strength represented by all of you in this room 
must be mobilized to demonstrate collective resolve and make clear 
our intention not to yield to aggression brady said 
officials said that while the united states was pushing for more 
than 14 billion in assistance for the frontline states of turkey 
egypt and jordan and other hardhit countries some european 
countries were insisting that a much smaller amount of around 9 
billion was all that was needed 
saudi arabia reportedly was objecting to including jordan as a 
beneficiary country until jordan moved more forcefully to close its 
borders to trade with iraq 
president bush put forward his proposal for the crisis 
coordination group during an address tuesday to the opening 
sessions of the 154nation international monetary fund and its 
sister organization the world bank 
while officials of the large donor countries indicated general 
support for a coordinating group they let it be known that many of 
the details remained to be worked out 
british chancellor of the exchequer john major told reporters 
that it was possible that a working group session today would be 
unable to resolve all the outstanding issues and would end up 
bucking the dispute to a later meeting of finance ministers 
it is clearly sensible for the world to get together and 
determine what should be the elements of assistance how much it 
should be and how that should be divided among the donor nations 
major said 
officials of japan which already has pledged 4 billion more 
than any other country outside of oilrich persian gulf nations 
indicated they had questions as well on how the informal 
coordinating council would work 
president bush gave one idea whether it will go ahead will 
depend on the response of the countries involved japanese 
finance minister ryutaro hashimoto told reporters late tuesday 
in his speech bush noted the refugee crisis as well as 
unemployment problems and serious economic disruptions resulting 
from rising oil prices 
this staggering burden which is pressing upon those most 
seriously affected countries calls for a generous response from 
the world community the president told the finance officials 
the political leadership of the un must be matched by the 
economic leadership of the imf and world bank he said 
the united states has been trying for a month to mobilize 
financial support to pay the cost of the us military buildup in 
the persian gulf and to compensate countries harmed by the un 
trade embargo against iraq 
the administration fears that the sanctions against iraq could 
begin to unravel without substantial economic assistance 
the united states has obtained pledges of 20 billion from the 
allies divided equally between support for the military effort and 
assistance for the three countries hardest hit by the turmoil 
turkey egypt and jordan the socalled frontline states 
however a west german official who briefed reporters on 
condition of anonymity said the united states now was seeking 
145 billion in aid for the frontline states up from an initial 
estimate of 105 billion earlier this month 
the german official said some european countries questioned 
whether this amount overstated the need he said his country also 
would like to see the donor pool widened to include such nations as 
switzerland and sweden 
in a fact sheet released by the white house the countries 
expected to participate with the united states in the crisis 
coordination group included japan west germany britain france 
canada italy saudi arabia kuwait the united arab emirates 
qatar and south korea 
