<TEXT>
vendors across the country went on 
brief symbolic strikes wednesday to protest government plans to 
sell their shops in auctions 
the expected sale will be the beginning of a comprehensive 
privatization process the cornerstone of the ongoing economic 
reform aimed at transforming the stateowned system of command 
economy into a westernstyle market mechanism 
the heads of the federal government and the czech and slovak 
republics plan to meet thursday with president vaclav havel in the 
moravian city of kromeriz 180 miles east of prague to complete 
work on the wording of the privatization law 
the law must then go to parliament for approval 
in the first round of what the government dubbed small 
privatization original owners may reclaim shops confiscated 
after the communists seized power in 1948 and nationalized private 
property 
shops and small enterprises not claimed by former owners will 
then be offered either to their employees or auctioned off to the 
highest bidder 
while an outsider will have to pay for the shop within seven 
days of the purchase a current employee will be given five years 
to pay up to 50 percent of the price 
this measure is designed to give vendors incentive to take over 
their shops and to compensate for the lack of cash available to buy 
enterprises outright 
vendors have protested the provision demanding a clear first 
priority on shops to be sold off 
if a guy comes to the auction and puts half a million crowns 
on the table there is no way i can compete with him even if i have 
state credit i can never handle a transaction worth that much 
money said vitezslav klement a vegetable vendor in pragues 
working class district of smichov 
shops to the vendors not moneychangers and communist 
mafia read a sign across an antiques shop window wednesday 
shops shut down for anything between five minutes to an hour in 
wednesdays protest strike against the privatization laws 
large savings were exceptional in czechoslovakias centrally 
planned economy where monthly wages averaged 3200 crowns or 
about 200 
those who thrived on the black market and other components of 
the shadow economy tolerated by communists have saved millions 
often in convertible currencies stashed in western banks 
shop vendors claim the auctions would put an abrupt end to the 
already poor network of food and services with the new owners 
likely to switch to the sale of electronics and other consumer 
goods that turn a fast profit 
the government says the most important thing is to privatize the 
economy as quickly as possible the government of the czech 
republic wants small privatization completed by dec 31 
its not so important who gets the actual shop what matters 
is the earliest possible occurrence of private ownership without 
which a free society cannot exist the mlada fronta daily which 
is known for its support of the reforms of finance minister vaclav 
klaus said wednesday 
privatization of large industrial plants and the agricultural 
sector is expected to start in early 1991 when the legislative 
framework giving access to foreign capital is ready and prices are 
decontrolled 
