a law professor testified wednesday that neil bush 
adequately informed fellow silverado savings and loan directors of 
his dealings with a developer who got a 900000 line of credit 
from the thrift 
a federal office of thrift supervision official however 
implied in testimony at an administrative hearing that president 
bushs son could have been more forthright with the silverado board 
about his relationship with denver developer kenneth good 
and another law professor said bushs actions as a silverado 
board member were unsafe unethical and unreasonable 
geoffrey c hazard jr a yale law professor summoned as an 
expert witness by bushs lawyer said bush a silverado director 
from 1985 to 1988 gave the board enough information 
he said bush told the board he had business dealings with good 
before the board approved the line of credit for good international 
inc a partnership formed by bush and good bush abstained from 
voting on the line of credit which he and good never used 
the office of thrift supervision has alleged that bush as a 
silverado director improperly voted on loans and credit for good 
and bill walters another denver developer who invested in bushs 
oil and gas exploration company 
good and walters eventually defaulted on more than 132 million 
in loans from the thrift silverado collapsed in late 1988 at a 
cost to taxpayers of 1 billion 
the hearing which could lead to bush being banned from the 
banking and savings industry began tuesday 
bush 35 has not yet attended the hearing he is scheduled to 
be the last witness to testify probably thursday his lawyer 
james nesland said bush wouldnt invoke his fifth amendment right 
against selfincrimination 
he will testify and he will answer all the questions he is 
asked nesland said 
on tuesday former silverado chairman michael wise the 
hearings leadoff witness invoked the fifth amendment 14 times 
when questioned in the judges chambers about his knowledge of 
bushs business dealings 
appearing with bush will be another former silverado director 
denver car dealer florian barth who refused to testify tuesday 
but changed his mind attorneys said wednesday 
government counsel stephen hershkowitz told administrative law 
judge daniel j davidson that barth had decided to appear before 
the hearing thursday morning davidson had threatened to subpoena 
barth 
hazard testified he was unsure how much bush actually told the 
board about the relationship but it was sufficient that he told 
them he was in business with mr good 
hazard said he believed directors need to consider state laws 
and legal opinions to gain insight into what their responsibilities 
are 
but terry sandefur the ots assistant deputy district director 
of supervision in topeka kan said tuesday he was not as certain 
as hazard that the disclosure was adequate he implied that bush 
may not have told the board all that he could have 
nesland pressed sandefur on the issue he said silverados 
investment committee and the board itself with bush abstaining 
approved the line of credit unanimously 
no doubt at the board meeting the transaction was found to 
be in the best interests of silverado bushs lawyer said 
maybe they perceived it to be in the best interests of 
silverado sandefur said emphasizing perceived 
edward g conry a law professor at the university of colorado 
and a witness for the office of thrift supervision said bushs 
actions were unsafe unethical and unreasonable 
his capacity to exercise impartial judgment was diminished 
because of his relationship with mr walters conry said he said 
bush put his selfinterest above silverados 
nesland irritated asked conry are you a mindreader 
i can see a vivid conflict of interest as well as anyone else 
can conry said 
on tuesday russell murray a former silverado executive vice 
president discussed his review of the 900000 line of credit for 
good international he testified he did not recall anyone 
questioning it even though good and bush had a business 
relationship 
he said he discussed the request with bush good and silverado 
chairman michael wise and then wrote a memo to the thrifts 
directors about the relationship before they approved the line of 
credit 
but he said that he did not have all the details of the 
relationship and that he would have asked for a legal opinion if he 
had had all the facts 
after the hearing davidson and ots officials will examine the 
testimony and then recommend whether any action should be taken 
against bush 
last week the federal deposit insurance corp sued bush and 
other former silverado directors for 200 million the lawsuit 
which also named wise and barth alleged gross negligence on the 
part of silverado directors contributed to the sampls collapse 
