a federal judge granted greyhound lines a 
48day extension to file its financial reorganization plan the 
dallasbased bus company announced wednesday 
the ruling by us bankruptcy judge richard s schmidt extends 
the deadline from oct 2 to nov 19 
on june 4 greyhound lines filed for protection under chapter 11 
of federal bankruptcy laws under federal law it has the exclusive 
right to present a plan of financial reorganization for 120 days 
that period ends oct 2 
we appreciate the courts vote of confidence in giving us this 
brief extension said j michael doyle senior vice president and 
chief financial officer of greyhound 
in june july and august the companys cash flow earnings 
before interest taxes and depreciation was 372 million 1016 
million and 1180 million respectively the company reported 
for the week ended sept 23 the company had ticket sales equal 
to 942 percent of the comparable week last year 
in many large complicated cases such as ours companies often 
stay in chapter 11 for two or three years or even longer said 
george w hanthorn senior vice president and general counsel of 
greyhound 
the company has indicated it expects to complete its 
reorganization plan before thanksgiving 
we have no plans to ask for additional time hanthorn said 
barring an unforeseen emergency our plan will be submitted to 
the court no later than november 19 
